INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('arm', '[아암]\n팔, 무기, 소매\n(의자의) 팔걸이, (조직의) 부분\n무장시키다', 'Your arms are the two long parts of your body that are attached to your shoulders and that have your hands at the end.\nThe arm of a piece of clothing is the part of it that covers your arm.\nThe arm of a chair is the part on which you rest your arm when you are sitting down.\nAn arm of an object is a long thin part of it that sticks out from the main part.\nAn arm of land or water is a long thin area of it that is joined to a broader area.\nArms are weapons, especially bombs and guns.\nThe arms of a city or of a noble family are its coat of arms. Arms is often used in the names of British pubs.\nIf you arm someone with a weapon, you provide them with a weapon.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armed', '[아r암d]\n무기가 사용되는, 무기/총을 소지한\n(지식 등으로) 무장한', 'Someone who is armed is carrying a weapon, usually a gun.\nAn armed attack or conflict involves people fighting with guns or carrying weapons.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armed resistance', '무력에 의한 저항', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armistice', '[^아r미s디s]\n휴전(협정)', 'An armistice is an agreement between countries who are at war with one another to stop fighting and to discuss ways of making peace.\nIn the United States, Veterans Day is a national holiday held on November 11. On that day in 1918, all sides in World War I stopped fighting. Americans originally called this holiday Armistice Day.\n', 0, '2016-11-15');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armload', '[암로-d]\n한 아름(의 양)', 'An armload of something is the same as an armful of something.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armor', '[아r뭐r]\n갑옷, 갑주\n~에게 갑옷을 입히다', '(armour)\nIn former times, armour was special metal clothing that soldiers wore for protection in battle.\nArmour consists of tanks and other military vehicles used in battle.\nArmour is a hard, usually metal, covering that protects a vehicle against attack.\nHIs horse was dressed all in green-from the armor that covered his head to the cloth that hung from his saddle.\nHe caught sight of armor glinting in the sunlight.\n', 0, '2016-09-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armory', '[아r뭐뤼]\n무기고, 병기 공장, ', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armpit', '[아r암핏t]\n겨드랑이, 싫은 장소, 더러운 곳', 'Your armpits are the areas of your body under your arms where your arms join your shoulders.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('armpit hair', '겨드랑이 털', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('army', '[아r-미]\n육군, 군대\n(특정 목적을 위한 사람들) 부대/집단', 'An army is a large organized group of people who are armed and trained to fight on land in a war. Most armies are organized and controlled by governments.\nAn army of people, animals, or things is a large number of them, especially when they are regarded as a force of some kind.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('around', '[어롸운d]\n약, ~ 쯤,\n사방에서, 빙 둘러, \n굴러서, 둘레(수치가) ~인,\n이리저리, 여기저기, 하릴없이\n주변에 있는, 마련할 수 있는,\n둘레에, 주위에, 둥굴게, 빙 돌아', 'around / round / about\nTo be positioned around a place or object means to surround it or be on all sides of it. To move around a place means to go along its edge, back to your starting point.\nIf you move around a corner or obstacle, you move to the other side of it. If you look around a corner or obstacle, you look to see what is on the other side.\nIf you move around a place, you travel through it, going to most of its parts. If you look around a place, you look at every part of it.\nIf someone moves around a place, they move through various parts of that place without having any particular destination.\nYou use around to say that something happens in different parts of a place or area.\nThe people around you are the people who you come into contact with, especially your friends and relatives, and the people you work with.\nIf something such as a film, a discussion, or a plan is based around something, that thing is its main theme.\nWhen you are giving measurements, you can use around to talk about the distance along the edge of something round.\nIf you turn around, you turn so that you are facing in the opposite direction.\nIf you go around to someone''s house, you visit them.\nYou use around in expressions such as sit around and hang around when you are saying that someone is spending time in a place and not doing anything very important.\nIf you move things around, you move them so that they are in different places.\nYou use around in expressions such as this time around or to come around when you are describing something that has happened before or things that happen regularly.\nThe villagers gathered around.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('around and around', '빙글빙글', 'They just kept going around and around in their joyous circle.\n', 0, '2016-09-29');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('around the clock', '하루 종일\n24시간 내내', 'for twenty-four hours without stopping\n', 0, '2016-10-17');
