INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('counterpart', '대응관계에 있는 사람, ', 'Someone''s or something''s counterpart is another person or thing that has a similar function or position in a different place.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('countless', '[카운t륏s]\n무수한, 셀수없이 많은', 'Countless means very many.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('country', '[컨츄뤼]\n나라, 국가\n(특정한 특징이 있는) 지역, 고장, 시골, 전원', 'country / landscape / countryside / terrain / land / scenery\nA country is one of the political units which the world is divided into, covering a particular area of land.\nThe people who live in a particular country can be referred to as the country.\nThe country consists of places such as farms, open fields, and villages which are away from towns and cities.\nA particular kind of country is an area of land which has particular characteristics or is connected with a particular well-known person.\nCountry music is popular music from the southern United States.\nIf you travel across country, you travel through country areas, avoiding major roads and towns.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('countryside', '[^컨츄뤼싸이d]\n시골, 지방, 교외', 'country / landscape / countryside / terrain / land / scenery\nThe countryside is land which is away from towns and cities.\nHe felt calm and safe as the stag sped like a white comet throught the wintry countryside.\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('couple', '연결하다, 짝이되다\n커플', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('courage', '용기, 대담함', 'Courage is the quality shown by someone who decides to do something difficult or dangerous, even though they may be afraid.\nIf you have the courage of your convictions, you have the confidence to do what you believe is right, even though other people may not agree or approve.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('courageous', '용감한', 'Someone who is courageous shows courage.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('courageously', '용감하게/대담하게', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('courageousness', '용감함, 대담함', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('course', '[코오r-s]\n진행, (배나 비행기의) 항로, 주행로\n(특정 과목에 대한 일련의) 강의, 강좌, (학)과목\n(대학의 교육) 과정, 추이, 전개', 'course / program\nCourse is often used in the expression ''of course'', or instead of ''of course'' in informal spoken English. See of course.\nThe course of a vehicle, especially a ship or aircraft, is the route along which it is travelling.\nA course of action is an action or a series of actions that you can do in a particular situation.\nYou can refer to the way that events develop as, for example, the course of history or the course of events.\nA course of medical treatment is a series of treatments that a doctor gives someone.\nIn sport, a course is an area of land where races are held or golf is played, or the land over which a race takes place.\nThe course of a river is the channel along which it flows.\nIf something happens in the course of a particular period of time, it happens during that period of time.\nIf you are on course for something, you are likely to achieve it.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('court defeat', '패배를 초래하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('court popularity', '인기를 얻으려고 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('courtyard', '[코rt야rd]\n(보통 성, 저택 등에서 건물로 둘러싸인)안마당, 안뜨리', 'A courtyard is an open area of ground which is surrounded by buildings or walls.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cousin', '[^커즌]\n사촌, 조카\n(먼) 일가, 친척\n형제같은 사람들', 'Your cousin is the child of your uncle or aunt.\nMorgan and Merlin do not even know I have it. A forest sprite, a cousin of my mother''s, gave it to me, in case I was ever in urgent need.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cove', '작은 만, 후미진 곳, ', 'A cove is a part of a coast where the land curves inwards so that the sea is partly enclosed.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cover', '[커버r]\n~을 덮다, 가리다, 취재하다, 대신하다\n덮개, 표지, 험호, 취장, 속임수\n(감추거나 보호하기 위해) 씌우다, 가리다\n다루다, 포함시키다\n(사람이 비운 자리를) 대신하다', 'hide / conceal / cover / disguise / mask / camouflage\nIf you cover something, you place something else over it in order to protect it, hide it, or close it.\nIf one thing covers another, it has been placed over it in order to protect it, hide it, or close it.\nIf one thing covers another, it forms a layer over its surface.\nTo cover something with or in something else means to put a layer of the second thing over its surface.\nIf you cover a particular distance, you travel that distance.\nTo cover someone or something means to protect them from attack, for example by pointing a gun in the direction \nAn insurance policy that covers a person or thing guarantees that money will be paid by the insurance company in relation to that person or thing.\nIf a law covers a particular set of people, things, or situations, it applies to them.\nCover is trees, rocks, or other places where you shelter from the weather or from an attack, or hide from someone.\nInsurance cover is a guarantee from an insurance company that money will be paid by them if it is needed.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cover for', '~을 대신하다, ~을 보호하다', 'Can you cover for me this Wednesday through Friday?\n', 0, '2016-09-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cover something up', '~을 완전히 덮다, 가리다\n(범행, 실수 등을) 숨기다, 은폐하다', 'to put something over somebody/something in order to hide or protect them/it\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cover up', '옷을 더 껴입다', 'to try hard to stop people finding out about a mistake, a crime, etc.; to hide the truth about something\nto put on more clothes\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cow', '소, 젖소, 암소', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('coward', '[코우워d]\n겁쟁이, 비겁자', 'If you call someone a coward, you disapprove of them because they are easily frightened and avoid dangerous or difficult situations.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('coward blow', '비겁한 공격', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cowherd', '[카우허r-d]\n소 치는 사람', 'a person employed to tend cattle\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('coyote', '[카요우디]\n코요테', 'A coyote is a small wolf which lives in the plains of North America.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cozy', '[^코우지]\n보온용 커버, (차양있는) 2인용 팔걸이 의자\n아늑한, 편안한, ', 'A house or room that is cosy is comfortable and warm.\nIf you are cosy, you are comfortable and warm.\nYou use cosy to describe activities that are pleasant and friendly, and involve people who know each other well.\nIt''s not very cozy today. / I felt cozy sitting by the fire.\nThis one looked cozy and safe and worm.\n', 0, '2016-11-22');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cozy up to somebody', '(특히 자기에게 쓸모가 있을 것 같은 사람에게)\n친하게 굴다', 'to try to become friendly with somebody, especially in order to gain an advantage for yourself\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crab', '[k뢥b]\n게', 'A crab is a sea creature with a flat round body covered by a shell, and five pairs of legs with large claws on the front pair. Crabs usually move sideways.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crab about', '~에 대해 투덜대다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crack', '[k^뤡k]\n갈라지다, 금이가다, 깨지다\n(짧고 세게) 때리다, 찧다\n갈라지는 소리가 나다\n(목소리가) 갈라지다, 잠기다\n(압박을 받아) 제 기능을 못하다, 무너지다\n날카로운 소리, 균열, 금, 결함', 'If something hard cracks, or if you crack it, it becomes slightly damaged, with lines appearing on its surface.\nIf something cracks, or if you crack it, it makes a sharp sound like the sound of a piece of wood breaking.\nIf you crack a hard part of your body, such as your knee or your head, you hurt it by accidentally hitting it hard against something.\nWhen you crack something that has a shell, such as an egg or a nut, you break the shell in order to reach the inside part.\nIf you crack a problem or a code, you solve it, especially after a lot of thought.\nIf someone cracks, they lose control of their emotions or actions because they are under a lot of pressure.\nIf your voice cracks when you are speaking or singing, it changes in pitch because you are feeling a strong emotion.\nIf you crack a joke, you tell it.\nThen she and Jack squeezed through the narrow crack and strode through the bright crystal cave.\n', 0, '2016-10-20');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crack down', '엄중 단속하다', 'to try harder to prevent people breaking a rule, using something harmful, committing a crime, etc. and deal severely with those who do\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crack down on', '~에 단호한 조취를 취하다, \n~을 엄중 단속하다, 탄압하다\n~을 통렬하게 비난하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crack the whip', '채찍을 휘두르다, (사람들을 볶아대다)', 'use your authority or power to make somebody work very hard, usually by treating them in a strict way\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crack up', '(중압감을 못 이기고 정신적으로나 육체적으로) \n무너지다/쓰러지다\n마구 웃기 시작하다', 'to start laughing a lot; to make somebody laugh a lot\nto become physically or mentally ill because you are under pressure\n"Hello, Mr. Toad," said Judy. She cracked herself up.\n', 0, '2016-10-20');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crackle', '[k뤠끌]\n(불꽃 등이) 탁탁 소리를 내다\n~ 을 탁탁 소리나게 하다', 'If something crackles, it makes a rapid series of short, harsh noises.\nHe heard a crackling sound.\nThe autumn leaves crunched and crackled under their leather shoes.\n', 0, '2016-09-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cradle', '[^k뤠이들]\n요람, 아기 침대, \n어린시절\n요람, 발상지\n부드럽게 잡다/안다', 'A cradle is a baby''s bed with high sides. Cradles often have curved bases so that they rock from side to side.\nThe cradle is the part of a telephone on which the receiver rests while it is not being used.\nA cradle is a frame which supports or protects something.\nA place that is referred to as the cradle of something is the place where it began.\nIf you cradle someone or something in your arms or hands, you hold them carefully and gently.\nIf something affects you from the cradle to the grave, it affects you throughout your life.\n', 0, '2016-11-17');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('craft', '기능, 기술, 공예, 솜씨, 작은 배, 비행기\n(특히 손으로) 공예품을 만들다, 공들여 만들다', 'You can refer to a boat, a spacecraft, or an aircraft as a craft.\nA craft is an activity such as weaving, carving, or pottery that involves making things skilfully with your hands.\nYou can use craft to refer to any activity or job that involves doing something skilfully.\nIf something is crafted, it is made skilfully.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('craftsmen', '장인', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('craggy', '[k^뤠-기]\n험준한, 바위투성이의\n우락부락하게 생긴', 'A craggy cliff or mountain is steep and rocky.\nA craggy face has large features and deep lines.\nWhen they came close to the craggy mountains, Jack was sure the stag would stop.\nIn the distance, a craggy mountain rose into the moonlit sky.\n', 0, '2016-10-06');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crake', '뜸부기', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cram', '[k뤰]\n(좁은 공간에 억지로) 밀어넣다, 쑤셔 넣다, \n(좁은 공간으로) 잔뜩 들어가다,\n게걸스럽게 먹다\n단기간의 집중(벼락치기) 시험 공부', 'If you cram things or people into a container or place, you put them into it, although there is hardly enough room for them.\nIf people cram into a place or vehicle or cram a place or vehicle, so many of them enter it at one time that it is completely full.\nIf you are cramming for an examination, you are learning as much as possible in a short time just before you take the examination.\n', 0, '2016-08-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cram away', '계속해서 주입식 공부하다, \n벼락공부를 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cram for', '~을 대비해서 버락치기 공부를 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cram into', '~에 쟁여넣다', 'to go into a place or space that is too small for everyone/everything; to push or force somebody/something into a place or space that is too small\n', 0, '2016-08-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cram up', '벼락공부하다', '', 0, '2016-08-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crammed', '가득 찬, 꽉 찬', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cramp', '[k^뤰p]\n(근육에 생기는) 경련, 쥐\n위경련\n(무엇의 발달이나 진행을) 막다, 방해하다', 'Cramp is a sudden strong pain caused by a muscle suddenly contracting. You sometimes get cramp in a muscle after you have been making a physical effort over a long period of time.\nIf someone or something cramps your style, their presence or existence restricts your behaviour in some way.\nThey have to warm up before they go into the water. If not, they can get cramps or even a heart attack.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crane', '두루미', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crank', '크랭크, \n(못마땅함) 괴짜, 화 짜증을 잘 내는 사람', 'If you call someone a crank, you think their ideas or behaviour are strange.\nA crank is a device that you turn in order to make something move.\nIf you crank an engine or machine, you make it move or function, especially by turning a handle.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crank back', '원상태로 돌아오다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crank call', '장난전화', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crank down', '끝나게 하다, 소멸시키다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crank in', '중요한 부분으로 짜넣다/포함시키다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crank out', '기계적으로 만들다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crap', '[k뢥]\n허튼소리, 헛소리,\n쓰레기 같은 것, 개 같은 수작\n똥, 똥누기', 'If you describe something as crap, you think that it is wrong or of very poor quality.\nCrap is sometimes used to refer to faeces.\nCraps or crap is a gambling game, played mainly in North America, in which you throw two dice and bet what the total will be.\nTo crap means to get rid of faeces from your body.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crap about', '바보같은 짓을 하다\n농땡이 부리다\n(시시한 일에) 구애되다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crap on', '업신여기다, 깔보다\n(남 을) 혼내주다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crap out', '실패하다, 망처놓다, 못쓰게 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crap up', '(일 따위를) 망치다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crappy', '형편없는, 거짓말 같은, 엉터리의', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crash', '[k뤠쉬]\n(자동차, 충돌, 항공기 추락) 사고, \n(무엇이 떨어지거나 부서질 때 나는) 요란한 소리, 굉음\n충돌하다, 추락하다, 붕괴하다\n충돌, 추락, 불시착', 'crash / slam / collide / smash / wreck\nA crash is an accident in which a moving vehicle hits something and is damaged or destroyed.\nA crash is a sudden, loud noise.\nIf a moving vehicle crashes or if the driver crashes it, it hits something and is damaged or destroyed.\nIf something crashes somewhere, it moves and hits something else violently, making a loud noise.\nIf a business or financial system crashes, it fails suddenly, often with serious effects.\nIf a computer or a computer program crashes, it fails suddenly.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crash o party', '파티에 초대받지 않고 참석하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crash out', '(경기에서) 탈락하다', 'to go to sleep because you are very tired\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crash over', '와르르 전복하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crash program', '단기 속성 계획', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crashing', '[k뤠싱]\n완전한, 절저한\n예외적인, 최고의\n놀랄만한, 두려울 만한', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crate', '[k뤠잇t]\n(물품 운송용 대형 나무) 상자, \n한 상자 (분량)\n(운송용 대형) 상자에 담다', 'A crate is a large box used for transporting or storing things.\nA crate is a plastic or wire box divided into sections which is used for carrying bottles.\nIf something is crated, it is packed in a crate so that it can be transported or stored somewhere safely.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crater', '[k뤠이더r]\n분화구, (폭탄 등에 의해 생긴) 큰 구멍', 'The land was filled with giant craters and tall mountains.\nOver time, their craters rose above the water.\n', 0, '2016-09-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crater lake', '화구호', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crave', '[k뤠이-v]\n갈망하다, 열망하다\n~을 간절히 청하다', 'If you crave something, you want to have it very much.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crave for', '~을 갈망하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crave pardon', '용서를 빌다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crawl', '[k로울]\n(엎드려) 기다, (곤충이) 기어가다, \n오싹해지다, 느릿느릿 다리다\n기어가기,  서행, (수영의) 크롤', 'When you crawl, you move forward on your hands and knees.\nWhen an insect crawls somewhere, it moves there quite slowly.\nIf someone or something crawls somewhere, they move or progress slowly or with great difficulty.\nIf you say that a place is crawling with people or animals, you are emphasizing that it is full of them.\nThe crawl is a kind of swimming stroke which you do lying on your front, swinging one arm over your head, and then the other arm.\nThe four real keepers of the cauldron crawled closer to Jack and Annie, hissing and snorting blue fire.\n', 0, '2016-10-01');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crawl out', '~에서 기어 나오다, ', 'She must have crawled out when we were looking at the paintings.\nA giant, slimy, mud-colored creature crawled out throught on of the doorways.\n', 0, '2016-09-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crawl up', '(옷이) 밀려 올라가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crawl with', '~으로 가득하다, 우글거리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crazy', '[^k레이지]\n미친듯한, \n(말이나 행동이) 정상이 아닌, 말도안되는\n미친 듯이 화가 난\n~을 대단히 좋아하는\n미치광이', 'mad / crazy / nuts / batty / out of your mind / (not) in your right mind\nIf you describe someone or something as crazy, you think they are very foolish or strange.\nSomeone who is crazy is insane.\nIf you are crazy about something, you are very enthusiastic about it. If you are not crazy about something, you do not like it.\nIf you are crazy about someone, you are deeply in love with them.\nIf something or someone makes you crazy or drives you crazy, they make you extremely annoyed or upset.\nYou use like crazy to emphasize that something happens to a great degree.\n', 0, '2016-10-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creak', '[k릑k]\n삐걱거리다, 삑삑 소리나다\n삐걱거리는 소리', 'If something creaks, it makes a short, high-pitched sound when it moves.\nSlowly the doors creaked open.\n', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('create', '[k뤼에잇t]\n창조하다, 창작하다, 만들어내다\n(어떤 느낌이나 인상을) 자아내다, 불러일으키다\n(계급이나 작위를) 수여하다', 'make / create / develop / produce / generate / form\nTo create something means to cause it to happen or exist.\nWhen someone creates a new product or process, they invent it or design it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('create panic', '공황상태를 야기하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creation', '창조, 창작, 창출, 창작품\n(성서에 묘사된 하나님의) 천지창조', 'In many religions, creation is the making of the universe, earth, and creatures by God.\nPeople sometimes refer to the whole universe as creation.\nYou can refer to something that someone has made as a creation, especially if it shows skill, imagination, or artistic ability.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creative', '[k뤼^에이디v]\n창조적인, 창의적인, \n독창적인\n창의적인 사람, (창작활동을 하는) 작가\n창의적인 것들', 'A creative person has the ability to invent and develop original ideas, especially in the arts.\nCreative activities involve the inventing and making of new kinds of things.\nIf you use something in a creative way, you use it in a new way that produces interesting and unusual results.\n', 0, '2016-10-06');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creature', '[k^뤼-춰r]\n생명이 있는 존재, 생물, \n생명체, 창조물, 사람', 'You can refer to any living thing that is not a plant as a creature, especially when it is of an unknown or unfamiliar kind. People also refer to imaginary animals and beings as creatures.\nIf you say that someone is a particular type of creature, you are focusing on a particular quality they have.\nA giant, slimy, mud-colored creature crawled out throught on of the doorways.\n"He''s a terrifying creature who comes from the Otherwordl," said Teddy.\nInstead, perched on the ledge of the nursery window was a horrifying creature.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('credentials', '[k뤠덴셜z]\n자격, 자격 인증서, 자격증', 'Someone''s credentials are their previous achievements, training, and general background, which indicate that they are qualified to do something.\nSomeone''s credentials are a letter or certificate that proves their identity or qualifications.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crediable', '명예가 되는, 영광스러운\n칭찬할만한', 'A creditable performance or achievement is of a reasonably high standard.\nIf you describe someone''s actions or aims as creditable, you mean that they are morally good.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('credibility', '진실성, 신용, 신뢰성', 'If someone or something has credibility, people believe in them and trust them.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('credit', '[k^뤠딧t]\n신용, 신용거래, (계좌) 잔고, 공제액\n명성, 학점\n~을 믿다, 인정하다, ~을 ~으로 여기다', 'If you are allowed credit, you are allowed to pay for goods or services several weeks or months after you have received them.\nIf someone or their bank account is in credit, their bank account has money in it.\nA credit is a sum of money which is added to an account.\nA credit is an amount of money that is given to someone.\nIf you get the credit for something good, people praise you because you are responsible for it, or are thought to be responsible for it.\nWhen a sum of money is credited to an account, the bank adds that sum of money to the total in the account.\nIf people credit someone with an achievement or if it is credited to them, people say or believe that they were responsible for it.\n', 0, '2016-11-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('credit to', '~에 입금하다', 'Assistant: We will credit it to your credit card account.\n', 0, '2016-11-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creek', '시내, 지류', 'A creek is a narrow place where the sea comes a long way into the land.\nA creek is a small stream or river.\nIf someone is up the creek, they are in a bad or difficult situation, or are wrong in some way. You can also say that someone is up the creek without a paddle.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creep', '[k륍]\n기어가다, 서행하다, 살금살금 움직이다\n네발로 기기, 서행, 몰래 다가가기', 'creep - crept - crept\nWhen people or animals creep somewhere, they move quietly and slowly.\nIf something creeps somewhere, it moves very slowly.\nIf you describe someone as a creep, you mean that you dislike them a great deal, especially because they are insincere and flatter people.\nThey crept between the huge trees and past hanging vines.\nShe was creeping over the dead leaves - right toward Annie.\nJank and Annie crept to the cave and peeked inside.\nThe sabertooth crept forward.\nThen he crept down the stairs\n', 0, '2016-10-27');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creep in', '~에 생기기/영향을 미치기 시작하다', 'to start happening or affecting somebody/something gradually\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creep on all fours', '네 발로 기다', 'He began creeping on all fours forward the buffalo.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creep out', '몰래 빠져 나가다', 'to make somebody feel frightened and not safe\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creep out of', '~에서 기어 나오다, ', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creep over', '~에 살금살금 다가가다,\n~위에 얽혀 퍼지다\n(공포 따위가) ~을 엄습하다', 'if a feeling creeps over you, or an expression creeps over your face, it gradually affects you\nA feeling of dread crept over Jack.\nA bitter chill crept over the room.\n', 0, '2016-09-28');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creep up', '(양, 가격 등이) 서서히 오르다\n기어 오르다', 'if a price, an amount, etc. creeps up, it rises very gradually\nto move nearer to somebody/something slowly and quietly without being seen or heard\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creeping rot', '서서히 진행되는 부패', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creepy', '[k뤼-삐]\n오싹하게 하는, 소름끼치는, 섬뜩한, 으스스한\n(곤충이) 기는', 'If you say that something or someone is creepy, you mean they make you feel very nervous or frightened.\n"It feels creepy to be invisible," she said.\n', 0, '2016-09-28');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creepy about', '~에 소름끼치는', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('creepy sensation', '징그러운 느낌', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crept', '[k뤱]\ncreep의 과거, 과거분사', 'Crept is the past tense and past participle of creep.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crescent', '[^k뤠센t]\n초승달 모양\n크레센트 (집이 죽 늘어서 있는 초승달 모양의 거리)', 'A crescent is a curved shape that is wider in the middle than at its ends, like the shape of the moon during its first and last quarters. It is the most important symbol of the Islamic faith.\nCrescent is sometimes used as part of the name of a street or row of houses that is usually built in a curve.\nHis partly eaten hamburger sat on the edge of his plate like a crescent moon.\n', 0, '2016-11-14');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crest', '[k뤠st]\n산마루, 물마루\n(닭) 벼슬, 관모, (말 등의) 목덜미, 갈기\n(특히 오랜 역사를 지닌 가문, 조직 등을 상징하는) 문장\n~에 깃장식을 달다\n꼭데기/정상에 이르다, 최고조에 이르다', 'The crest of a hill or a wave is the top of it.\nA bird''s crest is a group of upright feathers on the top of its head.\nA crest is a design that is the symbol of a noble family, a town, or an organization.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cretaceous', '[k릐테이셔s]\n백악기', 'of, denoting, or formed in the last period of the Mesozoic era, between the Jurassic and Tertiary periods, lasting 80 million years during which chalk deposits were formed and flowering plants first appeared\nthe Cretaceous the Cretaceous period or rock system\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crew', '[k루-]\n승무원, 선원, 동료, 패거리, 일당, 무리', 'The crew of a ship, an aircraft, or a spacecraft is the people who work on and operate it.\nA crew is a group of people with special technical skills who work together on a task or project.\nYou can use crew to refer to a group of people you disapprove of.\nIf you crew a boat, you work on it as part of the crew.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crib', '유아용, 침대, 구유(여물통)', 'A crib is a bed for a small baby.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cricket', '귀뚜라미', 'Crickets chirped loudly.\nCricket is an outdoor game played between two teams. Players try to score points, called runs, by hitting a ball with a wooden bat.\nA cricket is a small jumping insect that produces short, loud sounds by rubbing its wings together.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crickets chirp', '귀뚜라미가 울다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crime', '범죄, 죄, 죄악', 'A crime is an illegal action or activity for which a person can be punished by law.\nIf you say that doing something is a crime, you think it is very wrong or a serious mistake.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cringe', '[k^륀-쥐]\n(겁이 나서) 움츠리다, 움찍하다\n민망하다', 'If you cringe at something, you feel embarrassed or disgusted, and perhaps show this feeling in your expression or by making a slight movement.\n', 0, '2016-11-10');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crisis', '[k롸이씨s]\n위기, 문제, 사태, 혼란, 불황\n최악의 고비, 중대 기로', 'A crisis is a situation in which something or someone is affected by one or more very serious problems.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crisis eases', '위기가 완화되다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crisis over', '~에 대한 위기', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crisp', '[k릐습]\n(기분좋게) 바삭바삭한, 아삭아삭한,\n상쾌한, \n뽀드득뽀드득 하는, 바스락거리는', 'Food that is crisp is pleasantly hard, or has a pleasantly hard surface.\nWeather that is pleasantly fresh, cold, and dry can be described as crisp.\nCrisp cloth or paper is clean and has no creases in it.\nIf food crisps or if you crisp it, it becomes pleasantly hard, for example because you have heated it at a high temperature.\nCrisps are very thin slices of fried potato that are eaten cold as a snack.\nThe air felt crisp and cool.\n', 0, '2016-09-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crisp air', '상쾌한 공기', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('critic', '비평가, 비판가, 타인의 결정을 들추는 사람', 'A critic is a person who writes about and expresses opinions about things such as books, films, music, or art.\nSomeone who is a critic of a person or system disapproves of them and criticizes them publicly.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('critical biography', '평전', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('criticism', '비난, 비판, 비평, 혹평', 'Criticism is the action of expressing disapproval of something or someone. A criticism is a statement that expresses disapproval.\nCriticism is a serious examination and judgment of something such as a book or play.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('criticize', '비판하다, 비평하다, 비난하다', 'If you criticize someone or something, you express your disapproval of them by saying what you think is wrong with them.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('croak', '[k로욱k]\n(개구리나 까마귀가) 개골개골/깍깍 하다\n(낮고 거친 목소리로) 꺽꺽거리듯 말하다\n개골개골, 깍깍(하는 소리)', 'When a frog or bird croaks, it makes a harsh, low sound.\nIf someone croaks something, they say it in a low, rough voice.\n"ROK," the raven croaked.\nHe fluffed out his feathers and croaked, Wait, you guys!\n', 0, '2016-10-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crocodile', '악어 (아프리카산)', 'A crocodile is a large reptile with a long body and strong jaws. Crocodiles live in rivers and eat meat.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('Cro-Magnon', '크로마뇽인', 'Cro-Magnons scraped reindeer skins with flint rocks to make them soft.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crook', '[k^룩]\n사기꾼\n팔꿈치 안쪽, \n(손가락이나 팔을) 구부리다\n아픈, 병든', 'A crook is a dishonest person or a criminal.\nThe crook of your arm or leg is the soft inside part where you bend your elbow or knee.\nA crook is a long pole with a large hook at the end. A crook is carried by a bishop in religious ceremonies, or by a shepherd.\nIf you crook your arm or finger, you bend it.\nIf someone says they will do something by hook or by crook, they are determined to do it, even if they have to make a great effort or use dishonest means.\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crop', '[k뢉p]\n잘라내다, 수확하다, 경작하다\n농작물, 수확, 곡물\n(승마때 쓰는) 채찍\n머리를 아주 짧게 깍다, \n(사진이나 그림의 일부를) 잘라내다', 'Crops are plants such as wheat and potatoes that are grown in large quantities for food.\nThe plants or fruits that are collected at harvest time are referred to as a crop.\nYou can refer to a group of people or things that have appeared together as a crop of people or things.\nA crop is a short hairstyle.\nWhen a plant crops, it produces fruits or parts which people want.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crop up', '불쑥 나타나다, 발생하다', 'to appear, happen, etc. when it is not expected\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross', '[^k뤄s]\n십자, 십자가, 고난\n(가로질러) 건너다, 가로지르다, 교차시키다,\n서로 겹치게 놓다\nA와 B를 이종교배하다', 'angry / mad / indignant / cross / irate\nIf you cross something such as a room, a road, or an area of land or water, you move or travel to the other side of it. If you cross to a place, you move or travel over a room, road, or area of land or water in order to reach that place.\nA road, railway, or bridge that crosses an area of land or water passes over it.\nLines or roads that cross meet and go across each other.\nIf someone or something crosses a limit or boundary, for example the limit of acceptable behaviour, they go beyond it.\nA cross is a shape that consists of a vertical line or piece with a shorter horizontal line or piece across it. It is the most important Christian symbol.\nA shadow crossed the king''s face.\n', 0, '2016-11-15');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross over', '(문화, 음악, 정당 등이) (~으로) 바뀌다,', 'to go from one side of something, for example a road/street, a room, etc. to the other\nto move from one style or type of music, culture, politics, etc. to another; to combine parts of different styles or types\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross over into', '~쪽으로 넘어가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross over to', '~쪽으로 넘어가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross stitch', '십자수', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross the aisle', '변절하다, 전향하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross with', '~와 교배하다', '', 0, '2016-09-21');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross with somebody', '~에게 성을 내는', 'Now he was cross with Morgan.\n', 0, '2016-09-21');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crossbow', '쇠뇌', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cross-culture', '서로 다른 문화', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crosswalk', '횡단보도', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crouch', '[k롸웃취]\n숙이다, 구부리다, 쭈그리다, 움츠리다\n웅크린 자세, 움츠리기, 구부리기, 쭈그려 앉기', 'If you are crouching, your legs are bent under you so that you are close to the ground and leaning forward slightly.\nJack crouched below the window. / Annie crouched beside him.\nJack crouched down.\nCrouching down, he hurried toward her.\nJack and Annie crouched in the grass.\nThe bird was crouching, slightly spreading its wings.\nHidden in the shadows, they crouched together, their dark feathers touching.\n', 0, '2016-10-06');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crouch for shelter', '감추려고 웅크리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crow', '[^k로우]\n까마귀\n숫탉 울음소리(같은 소리), 환성\n(특히 이른 새벽에)''꼬끼오''하고 울다', 'A crow is a large black bird which makes a loud, harsh noise.\nWhen a cock crows, it makes a loud sound, often early in the morning.\nIf you say that someone is crowing about something they have achieved or are pleased about, you disapprove of them because they keep telling people proudly about it.\nRoosters crowed.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crow about', '~에 대해 우쭐해 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crow over', '~에 대해 우쭐해 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crowd', '[k롸우d]\n(길거리나 스포츠 경기장 등에 모인) 사람들, 군중, 무리, \n일반 대중, 보통 사람, 다수\n모여들다, 붐비다, (어떤 장소를) 가득 메우다', 'A crowd is a large group of people who have gathered together, for example to watch or listen to something interesting, or to protest about something.\nA particular crowd is a group of friends, or a set of people who share the same interests or job.\nWhen people crowd around someone or something, they gather closely together around them.\nIf people crowd into a place or are crowded into a place, large numbers of them enter it so that it becomes very full.\nIf a group of people crowd a place, there are so many of them there that it is full.\nIf people crowd you, they stand very closely around you trying to see or speak to you, so that you feel uncomfortable.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crowd around', '(~ 주위로) 모여들다\n(어중이떠중이가) 주변에 몰려들다, 운집하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crowd in', '떠오르다, 밀려들다', 'if high buildings, mountains, etc. crowd in, they seem to surround you and threaten you or have a strong effect on you\nto move in large numbers into a small place\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crowd out', '밀어내다', 'if a number of people or things crowd out other people or things, they are present in such large numbers that there is no room for anyone or anything else\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crowd something out', '(더 이상 공간이 없어) ~을 몰아내다\n~이 설 자리를 없게 만들다', 'if a number of people or things crowd out other people or things, they are present in such large numbers that there is no room for anyone or anything else\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crowded', '[k롸우딛d]\n(사람들이) 붐비는, 복잡한, 혼잡한, 꽉찬\n~이 가득한, 빡빡한', 'If a place is crowded, it is full of people.\nIf a place is crowded, a lot of people live there.\nIf your timetable, your life, or your mind is crowded, it is full of events, activities, or thoughts.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crowded with', '~로 복잡한, 붐비는', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crown', '[k롸-운]\n왕관, 왕위, 왕권\n화관, 월계관\n왕관을 씌우다, 왕위에 앉히다', 'A crown is a circular ornament, usually made of gold and jewels, which a king or queen wears on their head at official ceremonies. You can also use crown to refer to anything circular that is worn on someone''s head.\nThe government of a country that has a king or queen is sometimes referred to as the Crown. In British criminal cases the prosecutor is the Crown.\nYour crown is the top part of your head, at the back.\nA crown is an artificial top piece fixed over a broken or decayed tooth.\nWhen a king or queen is crowned, a crown is placed on their head as part of a ceremony in which they are officially made king or queen.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crud', '허풍, 과장, 변명', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crude forgery', '조잡한 위조품', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cruel', '[^쿠루-을]\n잔인한, 잔혹한, 무참한\n고통스러운, 괴로운', 'Someone who is cruel deliberately causes pain or distress to people or animals.\nA situation or event that is cruel is very harsh and causes people distress.\n"It''s cruel. You better let him go, or else!"\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cruel blow', '엄청난 일격', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cruel heart', '잔인한 기질', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cruel remark', '혹평', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('cruise', '[쿠르-s]\n유람선 여행, \n유람선을 타고 다니다, (꾸준한 속도로) 순항하다, 나아가다\n(특히 무엇을 찾아) 천천히 달리다, \n수월히 이기다/이루다', 'A cruise is a holiday during which you travel on a ship or boat and visit a number of places.\nIf you cruise a sea, river, or canal, you travel around it or along it on a cruise.\nIf a car, ship, or aircraft cruises somewhere, it moves there at a steady comfortable speed.\nIf a team or sports player cruises to victory, they win easily.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crumb', '[k^뤔]\n(빵, 케이크의) 부스러기, 작은 것, 약간, 소량', 'Bread crumbs\nCrumbs are tiny pieces that fall from bread, biscuits, or cake when you cut it or eat it.\nA crumb of something, for example information, is a very small amount of it.\nIt shone on a long banquet table. The table was littered with bread crumbs, candle wax, and the petals of dead flowers.\n', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crumble', '[k뤔벌]\n바스러지다, 바스러뜨리다\n(건물이나 땅이) 허물어지다, 무너지다', 'If something crumbles, or if you crumble it, it breaks into a lot of small pieces.\nIf an old building or piece of land is crumbling, parts of it keep breaking off.\nIf something such as a system, relationship, or hope crumbles, it comes to an end.\nIf someone crumbles, they stop resisting or trying to win, or become unable to cope.\nA crumble is a baked pudding made from fruit covered with a mixture of flour, butter, and sugar.\nShe crumbled the leaf into the chowder.\nThe volcanic rock crumbled and turned to soil.\n', 0, '2016-09-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crumble into', '산산이 부서져 ~이 되다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crunch', '[^k뤈치]\n아삭아삭 소리를 내는, 오도독오도독\n(시끄럽게) 아작아작/오도독 씹다\n', 'If you crunch something hard, such as a sweet, you crush it noisily between your teeth.\nIf something crunches or if you crunch it, it makes a breaking or crushing noise, for example when you step on it.\nIf you crunch across a surface made of very small stones, you move across it causing it to make a crunching noise.\nTo crunch numbers means to do a lot of calculations using a calculator or computer.\nYou can refer to an important time or event, for example when an important decision has to be made, as the crunch.\nA situation in which a business or economy has very little money can be referred to as a crunch.\nThe autumn leaves crunched and crackled under their leather shoes.\nJack, Annie, and Teddy crunched through fallen leaves until they came to Merlin''s oak.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crunch something up', '~을 완전히 으스러/우그러 뜨리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crunching', '오도독오도독', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crunchy', '[k뤈치]\n아삭아삭한, 바삭바삭한', 'Food that is crunchy is pleasantly hard or crisp so that it makes a noise when you eat it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crush', '[k^롸쉬]\n으스러뜨리다, 쭈그려뜨리다, \n눌러 부수다, 부서지다, 망가지다\n분쇄, 압착, 압도, 홀딱 반함, 일시적 열중', 'To crush something means to press it very hard so that its shape is destroyed or so that it breaks into pieces.\nTo crush a protest or movement, or a group of opponents, means to defeat it completely, usually by force.\nIf you are crushed by something, it upsets you a great deal.\nA crush is a crowd of people close together, in which it is difficult to move.\nIf you have a crush on someone, you are in love with them but do not have a relationship with them.\nThey used a crushed mild carton as a puck, hitting it back and forth the lenght of the table.\n', 0, '2016-10-25');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crush in', '(몸, 차의 일부)를 부수다\n(여럿이) 확 밀치고 들어가다, 밀어 넣다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crush on', '(이성하게) 반하다, 연정을 품다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crush out', '(~을) 부수고 나가다, 탈옥하다\n(~에서) 몰아내다, 짜내다\n(희망 따위를) 빼앗다\n(질병을) 박멸하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('crush up', '분쇄하다\n~을 구깃구깃 뭉개다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
