INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grass', '[g뢔s]\n풀, 잔디, 풀밭, 초지, 목장\n~을 풀로 덥다, 방목하다', 'Grass is a very common plant consisting of large numbers of thin, spiky, green leaves that cover the surface of the ground.\nIf you talk about the grass, you are referring to an area of ground that is covered with grass, for example in your garden.\nGrass is the same as marijuana.\nA grass is someone who tells the police or other authorities about criminal activities that they know about.\nIf you say that one person grasses on another, the first person tells the police or other authorities about something criminal or wrong which the second person has done.\nThe grass was the greenest green.\nShe pulled away from the circle and tumbled back into the grass.\n', 0, '2016-09-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grass something over', '~에 잔디를 덮다/깔다', 'to cover an area of ground with grass\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grassy', '[g뤠시]\n풀로 덮인', 'A grassy area of land is covered in grass.\n', 0, '2016-09-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grassy plain', '초원', '', 0, '2016-09-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grate', '[g뤠잇t]\n(강판으로) 갈다, 갈리다\n짜증나게 하다, 신경을 건드리다\n(두 물채가 부딪쳐) 삐걱거리는/긁히는 소시를 내다\n(난로안의 연료를 받치는) 쇠살대', 'A grate is a framework of metal bars in a fireplace, which holds the coal or wood.\nIf you grate food such as cheese or carrots, you rub it over a metal tool called a grater so that the food is cut into very small pieces.\nWhen something grates, it rubs against something else making a harsh, unpleasant sound.\nIf something such as someone''s behaviour grates on you or grates, it makes you feel annoyed.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grate against', '~에 문지르다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grate on', '~에 거슬리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grate upon the ears', '귀에 거슬리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grateful', '[g뤠잇풀]\n감사하는, 고마운', 'If you are grateful for something that someone has given you or done for you, you have warm, friendly feelings towards them and wish to thank them.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grateful to', '~에게 고마워하는', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grater', '강판(요리기구)', 'A grater is a kitchen tool which has a rough surface that you use for cutting food into very small pieces.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grave', '[g뤠이v]\n무덤, 묘, 죽음, 사망\n~을 새기다, 조각하다, 명심하다\n엄축한, 장엄한, 중대한, 심각한', 'A grave is a place where a dead person is buried.\nYou can refer to someone''s death as their grave or to death as the grave.\nA grave event or situation is very serious, important, and worrying.\nA grave person is quiet and serious in their appearance or behaviour.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grave accusation', '가혹한 비난', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grave ceremony', '엄숙한 식전', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gravy', '[g^뤠이비]\n그레이비(고기를 익힐 때 나온 육즙에 밀가루 등을 넣어 만든 소스)\n뜻밖에 얻는 것(특히 돈), 횡재', 'Gravy is a sauce made from the juices that come from meat when it cooks.\nToday''s choices featured a mystery meat covered in gravy.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gray', '[g뤠이]\n회색, 잿빛\n회색의, 창백한, 노년의', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grayish', '[g뤠이-쉬]\n회색이 도는, 희끄므레한', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('graze', '[g뤠이z]\n(소,양) 생풀을 뜯어먹다, 방목하다, \n(피부를) 까지게/긁히게 하다, 가볍게 스치다\n스치기, 벗겨지기, 찰과상', 'When animals graze or are grazed, they eat the grass or other plants that are growing in a particular place. You can also say that a field is grazed by animals.\nIf you graze a part of your body, you injure your skin by scraping against something.\nIf something grazes another thing, it touches that thing lightly as it passes by.\nA graze is a small wound caused by scraping against something.\nThe zebras were grazing in the grass.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('graze cattle', '소를 방목하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('graze livestock', '가축을 방목하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('graze stock', '가축을 방목하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grease', '[g뤼-s]\n지방, 윤활유(그리스), \n(굳어있는 동물성) 기름/지방', 'Grease is a thick, oily substance which is put on the moving parts of cars and other machines in order to make them work smoothly.\nGrease is an oily substance that is produced by your skin.\nGrease is animal fat that is produced by cooking meat. You can use grease for cooking.\nIf you grease a part of a car, machine, or device, you put grease on it in order to make it work smoothly.\nIf you grease a dish, you put a small amount of fat or oil around the inside of it in order to prevent food sticking to it during cooking.\nThe grease from the turkey sputtered and popped.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greasy', '[g뤼-쥐]\n기름투성이의, 기름이 많이 묻은, 기름을 많이 쓴\n지성인, \n(진실성이 안 느껴지게) 지나치게 정중한/칠절한', 'Something that is greasy has grease on it or in it.\nYou need to avoid highly fatty and greasy foods. You should also avoid too much sugar and caffeine.\nThe boy set a greasy slab of beef on a soggy piece of bread in front of him.\n', 0, '2016-09-26');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('great', '[g^뤠잇]\n(크기, 양이 보통 이상보다)큰, 많은, 엄청난, 대단한\n위대한, 정말 좋은, 중요한', 'big / large / great\nYou use great to describe something that is very large. Great is more formal than big.\nGreat means large in amount or degree.\nYou use great to describe something that is important, famous, or exciting.\nThe greats in a particular subject or field of activity are the people who have been most successful or famous in it.\nThe greats of popular modern music are records that have been successful and that continue to be popular.\nHe felt great telling their new friends about the tree house.\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('great aims', '고상한 목적', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('great emphasis', '특별한 강조', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('great line', '명대사', 'There were many great lines in the movie.\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('great word', '즐겨쓰는 말', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greater than', '~ 보다 크다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greater than or equal', '~ 보다 크거나 같다 (<=)', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greedy', '[g뤼-디]\n탐욕스러운, 욕심많은', 'If you describe someone as greedy, you mean that they want to have more of something such as food or money than is necessary or fair.\nThe gold-greedy pirates seemed to have lost their minds.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greedy up', '게걸스레 먹다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('Greek', '[g뤽k]\n그리스인, 그리스어', 'Greek means belonging or relating to Greece.\nA Greek is a person who comes from Greece.\nGreek is the language used in Greece.\nGreek or Ancient Greek was the language used in Greece in ancient times.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greenhouse', '[g륀하우s]\n온실', 'A greenhouse is a glass building in which you grow plants that need to be protected from bad weather.\nGreenhouse means relating to or causing the greenhouse effect.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greenhouse effect', '온실 효과', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greenish', '[g릐니싀]\n녹색을 띤', 'Greenish means slightly green in colour.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greet', '[g륏-t]\n인사하다, 맞이하다, 환영하다\n(특정한) 반응을 보이다, 받아들이다', 'When you greet someone, you say ''Hello'' or shake hands with them.\nIf something is greeted in a particular way, people react to it in that way.\nIf you are greeted by something, it is the first thing you notice in a particular place.\nWe say aloha when we greet our friends. And we say aloha when we leave them.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greet warmly', '정중히 인사하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('greet with', '~로 맞아들이다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grenade', '[g뤼네이d]\n수류탄', 'A grenade or a hand grenade is a small bomb that can be thrown by hand.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grin', '[g릔]\n(소리없이) 활짝/크게 웃다, \n밝게 생긋 웃다, (고통, 노여움으로) 이를 들어내다\n밝은 웃음, 방긋 웃음', 'When you grin, you smile broadly.\nA grin is a broad smile.\nIf you grin and bear it, you accept a difficult or unpleasant situation without complaining because you know there is nothing you can do to make things better. / Cap''n Bones grinned his black-toothed grin.\nCap''n Bones gave Jack a horrible grin. / He seemed to be grinning at them. / The monkey just grinned.\nJack grinned, "Me too" he said.\nHe grinned a big grin just like his sister''s.\nHe broke into a big grin.\n"No! But I should like to!" Teddy said with a grin.\n"I don''t know," said Teddy. Then he grinned.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grin and bear it', '(고통, 실망, 곤경을) 쓴웃음을 지으며 참다', 'accept something unpleasant without complaining\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grin defiance', '이를 드러내어 반항의 뜻을 보이다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grin from ear to ear', '입을 쩍 벌리고 싱글싱글 웃다', '', 0, '2016-09-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grin with', '~때문에 싱긋 웃다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grind', '[g롸인d]\n(곡식 등을 잘게) 갈다, 빻다\n(갈거나 빻아서) 생산하다\n(에디에 대고 ~을) 비비다, 문지르다\n(흔히 듣기 싫은 소리가 나게) 갈다, 삐걱거리다\n(시간이 오래 걸리는) 고된 일, 따분한 일', 'If you grind a substance such as corn, you crush it between two hard surfaces or with a machine until it becomes a fine powder.\nIf you grind something into a surface, you press and rub it hard into the surface using small circular or sideways movements.\nIf you grind something, you make it smooth or sharp by rubbing it against a hard surface.\nIf a vehicle grinds somewhere, it moves there very slowly and noisily.\nThe grind of a machine is the harsh, scraping noise that it makes, usually because it is old or is working too hard.\nIf you refer to routine tasks or activities as the grind, you mean they are boring and take up a lot of time and effort.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grind on', '(불쾌한 일이 오래) 끌다, 이어지다', 'to continue for a long time in a boring or unpleasant way\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grind somebody down', '(~에게 ~을 오랫동안) 고통을 주다, 학대하다', 'to treat somebody in an unkind way or annoy them for a long time until they can no longer defend themselves or fight back\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grind something out', '(흔히 좋지도 않은 것을 대량으로) 생산해 내다', 'to produce something in large quantities over a long period of time, especially something that is not interesting or of good quality\nto press a burning cigarette down firmly with your hand or your foot in order to stop it burning\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grind to a halt', '서서히(가다가) 멈추다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grind up', '갈아/문질러 부수다, 가루로 만들다', 'to break or crush something into very small pieces\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grinning skull', '이빨을 드러내놓고 있는 두개골', 'As he and Annie headed toward home, three creatures stepped onto the sidewak in front of them-a hideous witch, a grinning skeleton, and a huge hairy eyeball.\n', 0, '2016-10-08');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grip', '[g^륍]\n꽉 움켜잡음, 움켜쥠\n통재, 지배, 이해, 파악, \n접지력\n꽉 잡다, 움켜쥐다, \n(마음, 흥미, 시선을) 끌다, 사로잡다', 'hold / hold on / cling / clutch / grip / grasp / clasp / hang on\nIf you grip something, you take hold of it with your hand and continue to hold it firmly.\nIf you are gripped by something such as a story or a series of events, your attention is concentrated on it and held by it.\nA grip is a firm, strong hold on something.\nSomeone''s grip on something is the power and control they have over it.\nIf things such as shoes or car tyres have grip, they do not slip.\nA grip is a bag that is smaller than a suitcase, and that you use when you are travelling.\nJack gripped the sides of his board as he zoomed along with the others.\nHe leaped up from his chair and tried to grip her.\nGripping his pencil made Jack feel stronger.\nGripping the hazel twig in his beak, he stared down at Annie.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grit', '[g륏t]\n모래, 아주 작은 돌,\n투지, 기개\n빙판에 모래/소금 등을 뿌리다', 'Grit is very small pieces of stone. It is often put on roads in winter to make them less slippery.\nIf someone has grit, they have the determination and courage to continue doing something even though it is very difficult.\nIf you grit your teeth, you press your upper and lower teeth tightly together, usually because you are angry about something.\nIf you grit your teeth, you make up your mind to carry on even if the situation is very difficult.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grit teeth', '이를 갈다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grit your teeth', '이를 악물다, (포기하지 않기 위해) 이를 악물다', 'be determined to continue to do something in a difficult or an unpleasant situation\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groan', '[g로운]\n(고통, 짜증으로) 신음소리를 내다, 끙하는 소리를 내다, \n끙끙거리다, 불평하다\n(기뻐서) 탄성을 지르다. \n끙끙거리는 소리, 신음, 불만', 'If you groan, you make a long, low sound because you are in pain, or because you are upset or unhappy about something.\nIf you groan something, you say it in a low, unhappy voice.\nIf you groan about something, you complain about it.\nIf wood or something made of wood groans, it makes a loud sound when it moves.\nIf you say that something such as a table groans under the weight of food, you are emphasizing that there is a lot of food on it.\nIf you say that someone or something is groaning under the weight of something, you think there is too much of that thing.\nJack groaned.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groan in', '~으로 신음 소리를 내다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groan inwardly', '남모르게 괴로워하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groan over', '~에 대해 신음하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grocery', '[g뤄서릐]\n식료품, 잡화점', 'A grocery or a grocery store is a grocer''s shop.\nGroceries are foods you buy at a grocer''s or at a supermarket such as flour, sugar, and tinned foods.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grocery store', '식료품점', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groom', '[g룸]\n(동물을) 손질/솔질 하다, (가죽, 털 등을) 다듬다\n깔끔하게 하다, 반듯하게 손질하다\n신랑, 마부, 말 사육 담당자', 'A groom is the same as a bridegroom.\nA groom is someone whose job is to look after the horses in a stable and to keep them clean.\nIf you groom an animal, you clean its fur, usually by brushing it.\nIf you are groomed for a special job, someone prepares you for it by teaching you the skills you will need.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groom as', '~으로 준비시키다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groom for', '~에 대해 준비시키다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groovy', '[g루-비]\n멋진, 근사한, \n상투적인, 끝내주는, 연주가 훌륭한', 'If you describe something as groovy, you mean that it is attractive, fashionable, or exciting.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gross', '[g로우s]\n총계의, 전부의, 천박한, 상스러운\n역겨운, 아주 무례한\n세금 포함해서', 'disgusting / revolting / foul / repulsive / offensive / gross / nauseating\nYou use gross to describe something unacceptable or unpleasant to a very great amount, degree, or intensity.\nIf you say that someone''s speech or behaviour is gross, you think it is very rude or unacceptable.\nIf you describe something as gross, you think it is very unpleasant.\nIf you describe someone as gross, you mean that they are extremely fat and unattractive.\nGross means the total amount of something, especially money, before any has been taken away.\nGross means the total amount of something, after all the relevant amounts have been added together.\nIf a person or a business grosses a particular amount of money, they earn that amount of money before tax has been taken away.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gross behaviour', '아주 무례한 행위', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gross body', '뚱뚱한 몸', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gross somebody out', '~를 역겹게 하다', 'to make somebody feel disgusted\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grouch', '[g롸우츠]\n토라지다, 불평하다\n불평이 많은 사람, ', 'A grouch is someone who is always complaining in a bad-tempered way.\nA grouch is a bad-tempered complaint.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grouchy', '[g롸우치]\n시무룩한, 기분이 언짢은', 'If someone is grouchy, they are very bad-tempered and complain a lot.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('ground', '[g^롸운d]\n땅, 지면, 토양, 공터, 운동장\n지상의, 가루로 만든, 빻은\n(배가) 좌초되다, 이륙을 못하게 하다\n(자녀에 대한 벌로) 나가 놀지/외출하지 못하게 하다', 'floor / ground / land / earth / soil\nThe ground is the surface of the earth.\nIf you say that something takes place on the ground, you mean it takes place on the surface of the earth and not in the air.\nYou can refer to land as ground, especially when it has very few buildings or when it is considered to be special in some way.\nYou can use ground to refer to a place or situation in which particular methods or ideas can develop and be successful.\nIf an argument, belief, or opinion is grounded in something, that thing is used to justify it.\n"Are you grounded for a year? Off to jail? Can I have your room?"\n', 0, '2016-11-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groundbreaking', '[g롸운b뢔이킹]\n획기적인, 신기원을 이룬, ', 'You use groundbreaking to describe things which you think are significant because they provide new and positive ideas, and influence the way people think about things.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groundbreaking feats', '획기적인 업적', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groundbreaking idea', '획기적인 아이디어/기발한 생각', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('groundling', '[g롸운들륑]\n지상/지면 가까이 사는 동물/식물\n물밑에 사는 물고기, \n(엣 영국) 1층 바닥의 관람객, 저급한 관객, 저급한 사람\n지상 근무자', 'any animal or plant that lives close to the ground or at the bottom of a lake, river, etc\n(in Elizabethan theatre) a spectator standing in the yard in front of the stage and paying least\na spectator in the cheapest section of any theatre\na person on the ground as distinguished from one in an aircraft\n', 0, '2016-08-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('group', '[g룹p]\n불러 모으다, 분류하다\n그룹, 단체', 'A group of people or things is a number of people or things which are together in one place at one time.\nA group is a set of people who have the same interests or aims, and who organize themselves to work or act together.\nA group is a set of people, organizations, or things which are considered together because they have something in common.\nA group is a number of separate commercial or industrial firms which all have the same owner.\nIf a number of things or people are grouped together or group together, they are together in one place or within one organization or system.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
