INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grumpy', '기분이 언짢은, 심술이 난, 성격이 나쁜', 'If you say that someone is grumpy, you mean that they are bad-tempered and miserable.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grumpy about', '~에 대해 팩팩거리는', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grunt', '[g롼t]\n(돼지가) 꿀꿀거리다, 불평하다, 투덜거리다\n꿀꿀거리는 소리, 불평, 불만', 'If you grunt, you make a low sound, especially because you are annoyed or not interested in something.\nWhen an animal grunts, it makes a low rough noise.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grunt an answer', '투덜거리며 대답하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('grunt and groan', '툴툴거리며 끙끙거리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guarantee', '[게뤈^티-]\n굳은 약속, 확약, 품질 보증서, \n보증, 담보, 채무보증\n보증하다, 단언하다', 'If one thing guarantees another, the first is certain to cause the second thing to happen.\nIf you guarantee something, you promise that it will definitely happen, or that you will do or provide it for someone.\nIf a company guarantees its product or work, they provide a guarantee for it.\nSomething that is a guarantee of something else makes it certain that it will happen or that it is true.\nA guarantee is a written promise by a company to replace or repair a product free of charge if it has any faults within a particular time.\nB : Yes. We have a 7-day money-back guarantee.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guarantee for', '~기간 동안 보장하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guard', '[가r-d]\n경비요원, 보초, 감시, 경비, 수비\n지키다, 보호하다, 경비를 보다', 'If you guard a place, person, or object, you stand near them in order to watch and protect them.\nIf you guard someone, you watch them and keep them in a particular place to stop them from escaping.\nIf you guard some information or advantage that you have, you try to protect it or keep it for yourself.\nA guard is someone such as a soldier, police officer, or prison officer who is guarding a particular place or person.\nA guard is a specially organized group of people, such as soldiers or policemen, who protect or watch someone or something.\nOn a train, a guard is a person whose job is to travel on the train in order to help passengers, check tickets, and make sure that the train travels safely and on time.\nA guard is a protective device which covers a part of someone''s body or a dangerous part of a piece of equipment.\nIn the flickering torchlight, the guards looked like giants.\nThis must be the secret castle that guards the Diamond of Destiny!\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guard against something', '~이 생기지 않도록 조심/경계 하다\n~에 대한 대비책', 'to do something to prevent something happening or to protect yourself from something\nI''m guarding against the worst\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guard of honor', '의장병', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guerrilla', '게릴라, 유격대', 'A guerrilla is someone who fights as part of an unofficial army, usually against an official army or police force.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guess', '[게s]\n추축/짐작하다, 생각하다\n(추측으로) 알아맞히다/알아내다\n추측, 어림짐작', 'If you guess something, you give an answer or provide an opinion which may not be true because you do not have definite knowledge about the matter concerned.\nIf you guess that something is the case, you correctly form the opinion that it is the case, although you do not have definite knowledge about it.\nA guess is an attempt to give an answer or provide an opinion which may not be true because you do not have definite knowledge about the matter concerned.\nIf you say that something is anyone''s guess or anybody''s guess, you mean that no-one can be certain about what is really true.\nYou say at a guess to indicate that what you are saying is only an estimate or what you believe to be true, rather than being a definite fact.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guess at', '~을 맞혀보다\n짐작하다', 'to try to imagine something or make a judgement without knowing all the facts\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guest', '손님, 하객', 'A guest is someone who is visiting you or is at an event because you have invited them.\nA guest is someone who visits a place or organization or appears on a radio or television show because they have been invited to do so.\nA guest is someone who is staying in a hotel.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guide', '[^가이d]\n(어떤 주제에 대한 정보, 조언 등을 제공하는) 안내(서)\n관광 안내 책자\n(삶, 행동의) 인도자, 지도자\n지침, 지표\n안내하다, 지도하다\n안내인, 안내서, 도로표지', 'take / lead / escort / drive / show / guide / usher / direct\nA guide is a book that gives you information or instructions to help you do or understand something.\nA guide is a book that gives tourists information about a town, area, or country.\nA guide is someone who shows tourists around places such as museums or cities.\nIf you guide someone around a city, museum, or building, you show it to them and explain points of interest.\nIf you guide someone somewhere, you go there with them in order to show them the way.\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guild', '(직업, 관심, 목적 등이 같은 사람들의) 협회, 조합\n길드(중세 시대 기능인들의 조합)', 'A guild is an organization of people who do the same job.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guilt', '죄, 범죄, 유죄, 죄책감, (죄에 대한)책임', 'Guilt is an unhappy feeling that you have because you have done something wrong or think that you have done something wrong.\nGuilt is the fact that you have done something wrong or illegal.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guilt trip', '죄책감을 갖게 하려고 하는 말', 'things you say to somebody in order to make them feel guilty about something\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guilty', '최잭감이 드는, 가책을 느끼는,\n유죄의, 범죄적인', 'If you feel guilty, you feel unhappy because you think that you have done something wrong or have failed to do something which you should have done.\nGuilty is used of an action or fact that you feel guilty about.\nIf someone is guilty of a crime or offence, they have committed that crime or offence.\nIf someone is guilty of doing something wrong, they have done that thing.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guilty deed', '범행', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guise', '외관, 모습, 겉치레, 가장, 옷차림, 복장\n(흔히 평상시와 다르거나 가장된) 겉모습/외피', 'You use guise to refer to the outward appearance or form of someone or something, which is often temporary or different from their real nature.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('guitar', '[기^타r]\n기타', 'A guitar is a musical instrument with six strings and a long neck. You play the guitar by plucking or strumming the strings.\n', 0, '2016-10-25');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gull', '[가알]\n갈매기', 'A gull is a common sea bird.\n', 0, '2016-09-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gull into', '속여서 ~ 하게하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gull out of', '~에게서 속여서 빼앗다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gully', '(보통 시냇물이나 빗물에 의해 생긴) 도랑\n(깊은) 배수로', 'A gully is a long narrow valley with steep sides.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gulp', '[갈p]\n숨이 막히다, 목을 꿀꺽하다,\n꿀꺽꿀꺽 삼키다, 벌컥벌컥 마시다 \n(특히 공포, 놀라움에 질려) 침을 꿀꺽 삼키다\n꿀꺽꿀꺽 삼킴, 꿀꺽 마시기', 'If you gulp something, you eat or drink it very quickly by swallowing large quantities of it at once.\nIf you gulp, you swallow air, often making a noise in your throat as you do so, because you are nervous or excited.\nIf you gulp air, you breathe in a large amount of air quickly through your mouth.\nA gulp of air, food, or drink, is a large amount of it that you swallow at once.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gulp down water', '물을 꿀꺽꿀꺽 마시다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gulp something back', '(솟아오르는 감정을) 꿀꺽 삼키다/참다', 'to stop yourself showing that you are upset by swallowing hard\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gum', '[검]\n껌, 잇몸, 치은, 고무, 눈곱\n풀칠을 하다, (풀로) 붙이다', 'Gum is a substance, usually tasting of mint, which you chew for a long time but do not swallow.\nYour gums are the areas of firm, pink flesh inside your mouth, which your teeth grow out of.\nGum is a type of glue that is used to stick two pieces of paper together.\nIf two things are gummed together, they are stuck together.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gum a stamp down', '우표를 고무풀로 붙이다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gum something up', '(움직이거나 작동을 못 하도록 무엇에) \n끈적한 물질/접착제 을 발라 버리다', 'to fill something with a sticky substance so that it cannot move or work\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gun', '총, 무기, 출발 신호\n고속으로 돌아가다, ', 'A gun is a weapon from which bullets or other things are fired.\nA gun or a starting gun is an object like a gun that is used to make a noise to signal the start of a race.\nTo gun an engine or a vehicle means to make it start or go faster by pressing on the accelerator pedal.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gurgle', '[^거r걸]\n(물이 좁은 공간을 빠르게 흐를 때 나는 것 같은) \n쏴/콸콸 하는 소리가 나다\n(아기가 기분이 좋아 목에서) 까르륵 거리는 소리를 내다\n', 'If water is gurgling, it is making the sound that it makes when it flows quickly and unevenly through a narrow space.\nIf someone, especially a baby, is gurgling, they are making a sound in their throat similar to the gurgling of water.\n', 0, '2016-09-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gurgling', '콸콸/졸졸 흐르는\n목구멍을 울리는 소리로 말하는', 'He heard weird gurgling sound s behind them.\n', 0, '2016-09-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gurney', '바퀴가 달린 들것(침대)', 'A gurney is a bed on wheels that is used in hospitals for moving sick or injured people.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gush', '[가쉬]\n(액체가) 솟구치다, 쏟아져 나오다,\n(액체를 갑자기) 쏟아 내다\n(액체가 많은 양이) 솟구침, 분출', 'When liquid gushes out of something, or when something gushes a liquid, the liquid flows out very quickly and in large quantities.\nIf someone gushes, they express their admiration or pleasure in an exaggerated way.\nA gush of liquid is a sudden, rapid flow of liquid, or a quantity of it that suddenly flows out.\nWaterfalls gushed down their sides.\n', 0, '2016-09-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gush out', '콸콸 흘러나오다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gushy', '[가쉬]\n쏟아져 나오는, 분출하는, \n지나치게 감정적인, 과장된 말을 하는', 'displaying excessive admiration or sentimentality\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gust', '[^가st]\n세찬 바람, 돌풍, 돌풍, \n(물, 연기 등의) 갑작스런 분출, 격발, 폭발\n(바람) 급격하게 불다, 분출하다,\n(갑자기) 몰아치다', 'A gust is a short, strong, sudden rush of wind.\nIf you feel a gust of emotion, you feel the emotion suddenly and intensely.\nWhen the wind gusts, it blows with short, strong, sudden rushes.\nA gust of wind blew the canoe.\nA gust of wind shook the tree branches.\nA sudden gust of wind rustled the leaves.\n', 0, '2016-10-08');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gust a laughter', '와락 웃음이 터지다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gust of laughter', '와락 터지는 웃음', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gust of rage', '치솟는 분노', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gut', '[^갓]\n(특히 동물의) 내장, \n내용, 알맹이, 본질, 끈기, 용기, 배짱\n본능적인, 감정적인, 근본적인', 'A person''s or animal''s guts are all the organs inside them.\nThe gut is the tube inside the body of a person or animal through which food passes while it is being digested.\nGuts is the will and courage to do something which is difficult or unpleasant, or which might have unpleasant results.\nA gut feeling is based on instinct or emotion rather than reason.\nYou can refer to someone''s stomach as their gut, especially when it is very large and sticks out.\nGut is string made from part of the stomach of an animal. Traditionally, it is used to make the strings of sports rackets or musical instruments such as violins.\nWhen someone guts a dead animal or fish, they prepare it for cooking by removing all the organs from inside it.\nTo gut a building means to destroy the inside of it so that only its outside walls remain.\nIf you hate someone''s guts, you dislike them very much indeed.\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gut feeling', '직감', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gut reaction', '본능적인 반응', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gymnasium', '[쥠눼이지엄]\n체육관, 체조', 'A gymnasium is the same as a gym.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gymnastic', '체조, 정신적/지적 훈련\n훈련, 단련, 곡예', 'of, relating to, like, or involving gymnastics\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('gynecologist', '부인과의사, 부인과전문의', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('habilitate', '(특히 독일에서 대학 교수의) 자격을 얻다\n(사회 복귀를 위해) 교육[훈련]하다\n', 'to equip and finance (a mine)\nto qualify for office\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('habilitation', '훈련, 교육, 시설 투자', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('habit', '습관, 버릇, 관습, 경향', 'A habit is something that you do often or regularly.\nA habit is an action which is considered bad that someone does repeatedly and finds it difficult to stop doing.\nA drug habit is an addiction to a drug such as heroin or cocaine.\nA habit is a piece of clothing shaped like a long loose dress, which a nun or monk wears.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('habitat', '서식지, 거주지, 서식 환경', 'The habitat of an animal or plant is the natural environment in which it normally lives or grows.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hack', '[헤엑]\n(마구, 거칠게) 자르다/베다, 난도질하다\n(거칠게, 마구) 차다, 해킹하다\n(특정 사황에서) 버티다/못 버티다\n글쟁이, 일꾼', 'If you hack something or hack at it, you cut it with strong, rough strokes using a sharp tool such as an axe or knife.\nIf you hack your way through an area such as a jungle or hack a path through it, you move forward, cutting back the trees or plants that are in your way.\nIf you hack at or hack something which is too large, too long, or too expensive, you reduce its size, length, or cost by cutting out or getting rid of large parts of it.\nIf someone hacks into a computer system, they break into the system, especially in order to get secret information.\nIf you refer to a professional writer, such as a journalist, as a hack, you disapprove of them because they write for money without worrying very much about the quality of their writing.\nIf you refer to a politician as a hack, you disapprove of them because they are too loyal to their party and perhaps do not deserve the position they have.\nIf you say that someone can''t hack it or couldn''t hack it, you mean that they do not or did not have the qualities needed to do a task or cope with a situation.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hack at', '~을 마구 자르다', 'to try to cut something using strong rough blows with a knife, scissors, etc.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hack off', '몹시 화나게 하다', 'to make somebody feel extremely annoyed or irritated\nto cut something off something with rough heavy blows\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hack out', '~을 잘라내다, ~을 새겨 만들다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hack up', '난도질하다, 산산조각내다\n(간단한) 프로그램을 쓰다, 프로그램에 수정을 가하다', 'to cut something very roughly into large pieces\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hackish feature', '독창적인 기능', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haggle', '[^헤글]\n흥정하다, 옥신각신\n(특히 물건 값을 두고) 실랑이를 벌이다, 흥정을 하다', 'If you haggle, you argue about something before reaching an agreement, especially about the cost of something that you are buying.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haggle about', '~에 대해 입씨름 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haggle over', '~에 대해 입씨름 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haggle with', '~와 입씨름하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hail', '[헤일]\n~에게 인사하다, 환영하다,\n(신문 등에서 아주 훌륭하거나 특별한 것으로) \n묘사하다/일컫다\n(택시, 버스 등에[을]) 신호를 보내다/부르다\n(사람을[에게]) 부르다/소리치다\n인사, 환영, 싸라기눈, 우박', 'If a person, event, or achievement is hailed as important or successful, they are praised publicly.\nWhen it hails, hail falls like rain from the sky.\nSomeone who hails from a particular place was born there or lives there.\nIf you hail a taxi, you wave at it in order to stop it because you want the driver to take you somewhere.\nHail consists of small balls of ice that fall like rain from the sky.\nA hail of things, usually small objects, is a large number of them that hit you at the same time and with great force.\n', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hail a cab', '택시를 부르다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hail as', '~라고 부르며 맞이하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hail from', '~ 출신이다, ~에서 태어나다', 'to come from or to live in a particular place\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hailstorm', '[헤일s토r엄]\n우박을 동반한 폭풍', 'A hailstorm is a storm during which it hails.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hair', '[^헤어r]\n머리카락, 털, 섬유, 체모', 'Your hair is the fine threads that grow in a mass on your head.\nHair is the short, fine threads that grow on different parts of your body.\nHair is the threads that cover the body of an animal such as a dog, or make up a horse''s mane and ta\nIf you let your hair down, you relax completely and enjoy yourself.\nSomething that makes your hair stand on end shocks or frightens you very much.\nIf you say that someone has not a hair out of place, you are emphasizing that they are extremely smart and neatly dressed.\nIf you say that someone faced with a shock or a problem does not turn a hair, you mean that they do not show any surprise or fear, and remain completely calm.\nIf you say that someone is splitting hairs, you mean that they are making unnecessary distinctions between things when the differences between them are so small they are not important.\nTheir hair and beards were long and scraggly.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hairpiece', '[^헤어피s]\n부분 가발', 'A hairpiece is a piece of false hair that some people wear on their head if they are bald or if they want to make their own hair seem longer or thicker.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hairstyle', '[헤어s따일]\n(머리를 자르거나 매만져서 만든) 머리 모양, 헤어스타일', 'Your hairstyle is the style in which your hair has been cut or arranged.\n', 0, '2016-08-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hairy', '[헤이뤼]\n털이 많은, \n(흔히 흥미롭고) 아슬아슬한, 스릴 있는', 'Someone or something that is hairy is covered with hairs.\nIf you describe a situation as hairy, you mean that it is exciting, worrying, and rather frightening.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hairy chest', '털이 많이 난 가슴', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hairy problem', '어려운 문제', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hairy story', '섬뜩한 이야기', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('half', '[하f]\n절반, 1/2\n절반의, 부분적인\n절반 정도의, 반쯤, 약간, 다소', 'half / whole / quarter\nHalf of an amount or object is one of two equal parts that together make up the whole number, amount, or object.\nYou use half to say that something is only partly the case or happens to only a limited extent.\nYou use half to say that someone has parents of different nationalities. For example, if you are half German, one of your parents is German but the other is not.\nIn games such as football, rugby, and basketball, matches are divided into two equal periods of time which are called halves.\nHe half hoped their parents would say no.\n', 0, '2016-09-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('half and half', '반반씩, 반반으로', 'B : Well, can I make that a half-and-half pizza?\n', 0, '2016-10-25');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('half knowledge', '어중간한 지식', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('half the battle', '(일의 가장 중요하거나 힘든 단계인) 고비', '(complete, achieve, etc.) the most difficult part of something\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halfway', '[하f^웨이]\n(시간, 거리상으로) 중간의, 절반의\n중간쯤까지, 거의, 다소라도, \n부분적으로, 불완전하게\n꽤 괜찮은', 'Halfway means in the middle of a place or between two points, at an equal distance from each of them.\nHalfway means in the middle of a period of time or of an event.\nHalfway means reasonably.\nIf you meet someone halfway, you accept some of the points they are making so that you can come to an agreement with them.\n"We''re halfway there." said Jack.\nup the hillside was a ledge.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halfway between', '~ 사이의 중간에', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halfway measures', '어중간한 수단', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halfway point', '중간 지점', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hall', '넓은 방, 복도', 'The hall in a house or flat is the area just inside the front door, into which some of the other rooms open.\nA hall in a building is a long passage with doors into rooms on both sides of it.\nIf students live in hall in British English, or in a hall in American English, they live in a university or college building called a hall of residence.\nHall is sometimes used as part of the name of a large house in the country.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hall of fame', '명예의 전당', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hallow', '[^할러우]\n신성하게 하다, 깨끗하게 하다\n신성한 것으로 숭배하다\n신에게 바치다\n(고어) 성인', 'to consecrate or set apart as being holy\nto venerate as being holy\n"Halloween was called ''All Hallows Eve'' a long time ago."\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('Halloween', '[할러^위인]\n할러윈 (10월 31일 밤)', 'Halloween is the night of the 31st of October and is traditionally said to be the time when ghosts and witches can be seen. On Halloween, children often dress up as ghosts and witches.\n"Besides, you were a vampire last Halloween."\n"Halloween was called ''All Hallows Eve'' a long time ago."\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hallway', '[홀웨이]\n복도, 현관, 통로', 'A hallway in a building is a long passage with doors into rooms on both sides of it.\nA hallway in a house or flat is the area just inside the front door, into which some of the other rooms open.\nin AM, use entrance hall\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halt', '[할t]\n멎다, 정지하다, ~ 을 그만두게 하다\n중지, 정지, 휴지', 'When a person or a vehicle halts or when something halts them, they stop moving in the direction they were going and stand still.\nWhen something such as growth, development, or activity halts or when you halt it, it stops completely.\n''Halt!'' is a military order to stop walking or marching and stand still.\nIf someone calls a halt to something such as an activity, they decide not to continue with it or to end it immediately.\nThe stag finally came to a halt on the ledge of a steep cliff.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halve', '[헤-v]\n반으로 줄다/줄이다\n이등분 하다', 'When you halve something or when it halves, it is reduced to half its previous size or amount.\nIf you halve something, you divide it into two equal parts.\nHalves is the plural of half.\nThey whacked and whacked until their coconuts cracked into halves.\n', 0, '2016-09-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halve a apple', '사과를 이등분 하다', '', 0, '2016-09-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('halve the cost', '비용을 반감하다', '', 0, '2016-09-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('ham performance', '서투른 연기', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hammer', '~을 망치로 두드리다\n망치, 해머', 'beat / batter / pound / pummel / lash / hammer\nA hammer is a tool that consists of a heavy piece of metal at the end of a handle. It is used, for example, to hit nails into a piece of wood or a wall, or to break things into pieces.\nIn athletics, a hammer is a heavy weight on a piece of wire, which the athlete throws as far as possible.\nIf you hammer an object such as a nail, you hit it with a hammer.\nIf you hammer on a surface, you hit it several times in order to make a noise, or to emphasize something you are saying when you are angry.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hammer and tongs', '맹렬히 (싸우는, 다투는)', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hamper', '~을 저지하다, 방해하다\n큰 바구니, 식료품이 든 광주리', 'If someone or something hampers you, they makes it difficult for you to do what you are trying to do.\nA hamper is a basket containing food of various kinds that is given to people as a present.\nA hamper is a large basket with a lid, used especially for carrying food in.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hamper effort', '노력을 방해하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand', '[헨d]\n건네주다, 보내다, 집어주다\n손, 도움, (특정 상황에서의) 역할/영향력\n(시계) 바늘/시, 분, 초침\n(기계가 아닌) 사람 손으로 하는', 'Your hands are the parts of your body at the end of your arms. Each hand has four fingers and a thumb.\nThe hand of someone or something is their influence in an event or situation.\nIf you say that something is in a particular person''s hands, you mean that they are looking after it, own it, or are responsible for it.\nIf you ask someone for a hand with something, you are asking them to help you in what you are doing.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand away', '손을 뿌리치다,\n손을 빼내다', 'He yanked his hand away and knocked the spit off its legs.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand in', '제출하다, 손으로 건내다\n(과제물 등을) 제출하다[내다]; (분실물 등을) 인계하다', 'to give a piece of work to somebody, such as a teacher, so that they can correct, read or deal with it; to give something to somebody in authority because it belongs to them or is lost\nto tell somebody officially that you intend to leave your job\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand in hand', '손에 손을 잡고, 협력하여, 공동으로', 'holding each other''s hand, usually as a sign of affection\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand on', '넘겨주다', 'to pass to the next in a succession\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand out', '~을 주다, 나누어 주다, 분배하다', 'A handout is a gift of money, clothing, or food, which is given free to poor people.\nIf you call money that is given to someone a handout, you disapprove of it because you believe that the person who receives it has done nothing to earn or deserve it.\nA handout is a document which contains news or information about something and which is given, for example, to journalists or members of the public.\nA handout is a paper containing a summary of information or topics which will be dealt with in a lecture or talk.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand over', '이양하다, 인도하다, \n넘겨주다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand over hand', '손을 옮겨가며, 두 손을 번갈아', 'He went hand over hand.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand something on', '(남이 쓰거나 처리하도록) 넘겨주다, 남기다', 'to send or give something to another person after you have finished with it\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handcuff', '~에게 수갑을 채우다.\n수갑', 'Handcuffs are two metal rings which are joined together and can be locked round someone''s wrists, usually by the police during an arrest.\nIf you handcuff someone, you put handcuffs around their wrists.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handcuff to', '수갑을 채워 ~로 끌고가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handful', '[헨풀]\n줌, 움쿰\n몇 안되는 수\n다루기 힘든 사람/동물', 'A handful of people or things is a small number of them.\nA handful of something is the amount of it that you can hold in your hand.\nIf you say that someone, especially a child, is a handful, you mean that they are difficult to control.\nShe picked up a handful of stones and began throwing them at the birds.\n', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handful of', '소수의', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handful of men', '소수의 인원', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handful of sand', '모래 한 줌', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hand-held', '손바닥 크기의, 포켓용의, 손에 들고 쓰는\n(손에 들고 조작할 수 있는 정도의) 소형 기기, 휴대용', 'A hand-held device such as a camera or a computer is small and light enough to be used while you are holding it.\n', 0, '2016-11-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handicap', '(신체적, 정신적) 장애, 불리한 조건, \n불리하게 만들다', 'A handicap is a physical or mental disability.\nA handicap is an event or situation that places you at a disadvantage and makes it harder for you to do something.\nIn golf, a handicap is an advantage given to someone who is not a good player, in order to make the players more equal. As you improve, your handicap gets lower.\nIn horse racing, a handicap is a race in which some competitors are given a disadvantage of extra weight in an attempt to give everyone an equal chance of winning.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handicapped', '장애인\n(신체적, 정신적) 장애가 있는', 'disabled / handicapped\nSomeone who is handicapped has a physical or mental disability that prevents them living a totally normal life. Many people who have a disability find this word offensive.\n', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handkerchief', '[행커취f]\n손수건, (손수건 대용으로 쓰는) 화장지', 'A handkerchief is a small square piece of fabric which you use for blowing your nose.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handle', '[^헨들]\n(상황, 사람, 작업, 감정을) 다루다/다스리다/처리하다\n(차량, 동물, 기구 등을) 다루다, 손을대다\n(손으로) 만지다/들다/옮기다\n(문, 서랍, 창문 등을 열 때 잡는) 손잡이', 'A handle is a small round object or a lever that is attached to a door and is used for opening and closing it.\nA handle is the part of an object such as a tool, bag, or cup that you hold in order to be able to pick up and use the object.\nIf you have a handle on a subject or problem, you have a way of approaching it that helps you to understand it or deal with it.\nIf you say that someone can handle a problem or situation, you mean that they have the ability to deal with it successfully\nIf you talk about the way that someone handles a problem or situation, you mention whether or not they are successful in achieving the result they want.\nIf you handle a particular area of work, you have responsibility for it.\nWhen you handle something such as a weapon, vehicle, or animal, you use it or control it, especially by using your hands.\nIf something such as a vehicle handles well, it is easy to use or control.\nWhen you handle something, you hold it or move it with your hands.\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handle it', '감당하다, 처리하다', 'It was difficult, but she handled it today.\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handout', '인쇄물, 유인물\n(정부 등에서 주는) 지원금', 'A handout is a gift of money, clothing, or food, which is given free to poor people.\nIf you call money that is given to someone a handout, you disapprove of it because you believe that the person who receives it has done nothing to earn or deserve it.\nA handout is a document which contains news or information about something and which is given, for example, to journalists or members of the public.\nA handout is a paper containing a summary of information or topics which will be dealt with in a lecture or talk.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handsome', '잘생긴, 멋진, 보기 좋은,', 'beautiful / pretty / handsome / attractive / lovely / good-looking / gorgeous\nA handsome man has an attractive face with regular features.\nA handsome woman has an attractive appearance with features that are large and regular rather than small and delicate.\nA handsome sum of money is a large or generous amount.\nIf someone has a handsome win or a handsome victory, they get many more points or votes than their opponent.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handsome compliment', '아낌없는 칭찬', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handwriting', '[헨d롸이링]\n육필, 친필, (개인의) 필적', 'Your handwriting is your style of writing with a pen or pencil.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handy', '편리한, 도움이되는\n바로 가까이에, 곁에', 'Something that is handy is useful.\nA thing or place that is handy is nearby and therefore easy to get or reach.\nSomeone who is handy with a particular tool is skilful at using it.\nIf something comes in handy, it is useful in a particular situation.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('handyman', '잡역부, 숙련공, 사환\n(취미로나 직업으로) 집 안팎의 잔손질 보는 일을 잘하는 사람', 'A handyman is a man who earns money by doing small jobs for people such as making and repairing things in their houses. You can also describe a man who is good at making or repairing things in his home as a handyman.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang', '[^해앵]\n걸다, 매달다; 걸리다, 매달리다\n(느슨하게) 내려오다, 처지다\n(아래로) 늘어지다, 늘어뜨리다\n교수형에 처하다, 목을 매달다\n(그림 등을[이] 벽에) 걸다, 걸리다', 'If something hangs in a high place or position, or if you hang it there, it is attached there so it does not touch the ground.\nIf a piece of clothing or fabric hangs in a particular way or position, that is how it is worn or arranged.\nIf something hangs loose or hangs open, it is partly fixed in position, but is not firmly held, supported, or controlled, often in such a way that it moves freely.\nIf someone is hanged or if they hang, they are killed, usually as a punishment, by having a rope tied around their neck and the support taken away from under their feet.\n"Class, please hang your backpacks on the hooks and put your lunches in the cubbies," said Mr.Todd.\n', 0, '2016-10-20');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang limp', '늘어지게 매달다, 늘어지다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang on', '꽉 붙잡다, 단단히 매달리다, \n견디다, 버티다, \n(무슨 일을) 기다리다', 'hold / hold on / cling / clutch / grip / grasp / clasp / hang on\n(to somebody/something) to hold somebody/something firmly\nused to ask somebody to wait for a short time\nused to tell somebody to stop what they are doing or saying, because you have just realized something, or because you do not understand something\nto continue doing something even when the situation is difficult\nto wait for something to happen\n', 0, '2016-10-20');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang on something', '~에 달려있다.', 'to depend on something\n', 0, '2016-10-20');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang out', '어울리다, ~에서 많은 시간을 보내다, 서성거리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang out together', '붙어 다니다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang together', '잘 들어맞다, 일치하다, 일관되다\n단결하다, 협력하다', 'to be well organized and fit together well; to have parts that all agree with each other\nwhen people hang together, they support or help one another\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang tough', '완강히 버티다', 'be determined and refuse to change your attitude or ideas\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hang up', '전화를 끊다', 'to attach something from the top to a hook, a piece of string, etc. so that the lower part is free or loose; to be attached in this way\nto end a telephone conversation, often very suddenly, by putting down the part of the telephone that you speak into (the receiver) or switching the telephone off\nto finish using something for the last time; to give up a particular activity, profession, etc.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hangover', '[행오버r]\n잔존물, 유물, 후유증, 여파, 약의 부작용\n숙취', 'If someone wakes up with a hangover, they feel sick and have a headache because they have drunk a lot of alcohol the night before.\nSomething that is a hangover from the past is an idea or way of behaving which people used to have in the past but which people no longer generally have.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haphazard', '계획성 없는, 무작정의\n우연히, 아무렇게나, 되는데로, 무턱대고', 'If you describe something as haphazard, you are critical of it because it is not at all organized or is not arranged according to a plan.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('happen', '[^헤쁜]\n(특히 계획하지 않은일이) 일어나다, 발생하다, 벌어지다\n(무엇의 결과로) 일어나다/되다\n우연히 ~하다', 'Something that happens occurs or is done without being planned.\nIf something happens, it occurs as a result of a situation or course of action.\nWhen something, especially something unpleasant, happens to you, it takes place and affects you.\nIf you happen to do something, you do it by chance. If it happens that something is the case, it occurs by chance.\nYou use as it happens in order to introduce a statement, especially one that is rather surprising.\nHe hoped that happened before any ghosts showed up.\n', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('happen in', '우연히/불쑥 들르다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('happen on something', '~을 우연히 발견하다', 'to find or meet somebody/something by chance\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('happening', '[^하쁘닝]\n(흔히 이상한) 일, 사건\n(계획에 없던 예술적) 행위, 공연\n(장소가) 신나는, 멋진', 'Happenings are things that happen, often in a way that is unexpected or hard to explain.\nThey invite you to come with them to an outlying realm of Camelot where strange and eerie things are happening at a duke''s castle.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('happily', '행복하게, 만족 스럽게, 기꺼이, \n다행히도, 운 좋게도, ', 'You can add happily to a statement to indicate that you are glad that something happened or is true.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('happiness', '[헤삐니s]\n행복, 기쁨, 만족', 'satisfaction / happiness / contentment / fulfilment / glee\nJack felt a surge of happiness.\n', 0, '2016-09-21');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('happy', '(사람이) 행복한/기쁜, \n기꺼이 ~하는, ~하게 되어 기쁜\n운 좋은, 다행스러운', 'glad / happy / pleased / delighted / thrilled / overjoyed\nSomeone who is happy has feelings of pleasure, usually because something nice has happened or because they feel satisfied with their life.\nA happy time, place, or relationship is full of happy feelings and pleasant experiences, or has an atmosphere in which people feel happy.\nIf you are happy about a situation or arrangement, you are satisfied with it, for example because you think that something is being done in the right way.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harbor', '항구에 정박하다, 숨겨주다\n항구, 항만, 피난처', 'A harbour is an area of the sea at the coast which is partly enclosed by land or strong walls, so that boats can be left there safely.\nIf you harbour an emotion, thought, or secret, you have it in your mind over a long period of time.\nIf a person or country harbours someone who is wanted by the police, they let them stay in their house or country and offer them protection.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harbor an illusion', '환상을 품다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hard', '단단한, 굳은, 딱딱한, \n어려운, 곤란한/힘든\n열심히, 과도하게\n명백한, 엄연한\n(날씨가) 매서운/혹독한', 'hard / hardly\nSomething that is hard is very firm and stiff to touch and is not easily bent, cut, or broken.\nSomething that is hard is very difficult to do or deal with.\nIf you say that something is hard on a person or thing, you mean it affects them in a way that is likely to cause them damage or suffering.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hard dealing', '학대', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hard to tell', '구별하기 어렵다\n~를 알기 힘들다', 'It''s hard to tell whether Roger wants to go to a movie.\nTerry: We''ll get them back today. I think I did okay but sometimes it''s really hard to tell.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly', '[하r-d뤼]\n거의~할것같지 않다, \n거의~아니다\n막 (~하기 시작한) ~ 하자마자', 'hard / hardly\nhardly / scarcely / barely / no sooner\nYou use hardly to modify a statement when you want to emphasize that it is only a small amount or detail which makes it true, and that therefore it is best to consider the opposite statement as being true.\nYou use hardly in expressions such as hardly ever, hardly any, and hardly anyone to mean almost never, almost none, or almost no-one.\nYou use hardly before a negative statement in order to emphasize that something is usually true or usually happens.\nIf you say hardly had one thing happened when something else happened, you mean that the first event was followed immediately by the second.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly any', '거의 ~ 없는', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly at all', '거의 ~하지 않는 (almost not)', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly ever', '거의 ~하지 않는', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly know', '전혀 모른다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly less', '거의 같게', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly probable', '거의 일어날 것 같지 않은', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardly when', '~하자마자, ~ 하자 곧', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hardship', '[하r-d쉽]\n(돈, 식품등의 부족에서 오는) 어려움, 곤란', 'Hardship is a situation in which your life is difficult or unpleasant, often because you do not have enough money.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harm ', '손해, 손상, 불편\n해치다; 해를 끼치다, 손상시키다', 'damage / hurt / harm / impair / prejudice\nTo harm a person or animal means to cause them physical injury, usually on purpose.\nTo harm a thing, or sometimes a person, means to damage them or make them less effective or successful than they were.\nHarm is physical injury to a person or an animal which is usually caused on purpose.\nHarm is the damage to something which is caused by a particular course of action.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harmful', '(특히 사람의 건강, 환경에) 해로운, 유해한', 'Something that is harmful has a bad effect on something else, especially on a person''s health.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harmless insect', '무해한 곤충', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harmony', '조화, 일치, 화합', 'If people are living in harmony with each other, they are living together peacefully rather than fighting or arguing.\nHarmony is the pleasant combination of different notes of music played at the same time.\nThe harmony of something is the way in which its parts are combined into a pleasant arrangement.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harsh', '[하아r쉬]\n가혹한, 냉혹한, 혹독한, 거친, 냉엄한\n(너무 강하거나 밝거나 추해서) 눈에 거슬리는, 야한\n귀에 거슬리는, 듣기 싫은\n(손상을 줄 수 있을 정도로) 너무 쌘', 'Harsh climates or conditions are very difficult for people, animals, and plants to live in.\nHarsh actions or speech are unkind and show no understanding or sympathy.\nSomething that is harsh is so hard, bright, or rough that it seems unpleasant or harmful.\nHarsh voices and sounds are ones that are rough and unpleasant to listen to.\nIf you talk about harsh realities or facts, or the harsh truth, you are emphasizing that they are true or real, although they are unpleasant and people try to avoid thinking about them.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harsh land', '황량한 토지', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harsh on', '~을 부당하게 나무라다, \n~에게 잔소리 하다, 듣기 싫은 소리를 하다', 'to criticize somebody\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harsh voice', '귀에 거슬리는 목소리', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('harvest', '수확하다, 획득하다\n수확, 추수, 산물', 'The harvest is the gathering of a crop.\nA harvest is the crop that is gathered in.\nWhen you harvest a crop, you gather it in.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('has a point', '일리가 있다.', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hassle', '말다툼, 싸움, 소동\n귀찮은/번거로운 상황/일\n재촉하다, 들볶다', 'A hassle is a situation that is difficult and involves problems, effort, or arguments with people.\nIf someone hassles you, they cause problems for you, often by repeatedly telling you or asking you to do something, in an annoying way.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hassle about', '~에 대해 이러쿵저러쿵 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hassle over', '~에 대해 이러쿵저러쿵 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hassle with', '~와 이러쿵저러쿵 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haste', '[헤이st]\n(특히 시간이 부족하여) 서두름, 급함', 'Haste is the quality of doing something quickly, sometimes too quickly so that you are careless and make\nIf you do something in haste, you do it quickly and hurriedly, and sometimes carelessly.\n"Make haste!" he yelled.\n', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haste away', '급히 떠나다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hasty', '[^헤이s티]\n서두른, 성급한, (특히 좋지못한 결과를 나타냄)\n성급한, 경솔한', 'A hasty movement, action, or statement is sudden, and often done in reaction to something that has just happened.\nA hasty event or action is one that is completed more quickly than normal.\nIf you describe a person or their behaviour as hasty, you mean that they are acting too quickly, without thinking carefully, for example because they are angry.\n"But a warning, my boy: you are hasty and careless with your magic rhymes.\n', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hasty decision', '경솔한 결정', '', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hasty person', '조금한 사람', '', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hatch', '알에서 까다, 부화하다, \n(특히 비밀리에 계획등을) 만들어 내다, 기획하다\n부화, (항공기, 우주선의) 출입문', 'When a baby bird, insect, or other animal hatches, or when it is hatched, it comes out of its egg by breaking the shell.\nWhen an egg hatches or when a bird, insect, or other animal hatches an egg, the egg breaks open and a baby comes out.\nIf you hatch a plot or a scheme, you think of it and work it out.\nA hatch is an opening in the deck of a ship, through which people or cargo can go. You can also refer to the door of this opening as a hatch.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hatch a plot', '음모를 꾸미다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hatch out', '부화하다, ', 'when a bird, an insect, etc. hatches out, it comes out of the egg; when an egg hatches out, it breaks open and a bird, an insect, etc. comes out\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hate', '미워하다, 싫어하다\n강한 혐오', 'hate / hatred\nhate / dislike / can''t stand / despise / can''t bear / loathe / detest\nIf you hate someone or something, you have an extremely strong feeling of dislike for them.\nIf you say that you hate something such as a particular activity, you mean that you find it very unpleasant.\nYou can use hate in expressions such as ''I hate to say it'' or ''I hate to tell you'' when you want to express regret about what you are about to say, because you think it is unpleasant or should not be the case.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('hate out', '(미워하여) ~을 내쫓다, 따돌리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('haughty', '[^허-듸]\n거만한, 오만한', 'You use haughty to describe someone''s behaviour or appearance when you disapprove of the fact that they seem to be very proud and to think that they are better than other people.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
