INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('premiere', '[p뤼미어r]\n주요한, 눈에뛴는, 최초의\n(연극의) 초연, 초일, 첫날', 'The premiere of a new play or film is the first public performance of it.\nWhen a film or show premieres or is premiered, it is shown to an audience for the first time.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('premise', '[p뤠미s]\n(주장의) 전제, 근거, 부동산, 토지\n조건으로 하다, 가정하다', 'The premises of a business or an institution are all the buildings and land that it occupies in one place.\nA premise is something that you suppose is true and that you use as a basis for developing an idea.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('premise a remark', '전제를 놓다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('premises', '(한 사업체가 소유, 사용하는 건물이 딸린) 부지\n구내', 'building / property / premises / complex / structure / block / edifice\na piece of land together with its buildings, esp considered as a place of business\n(in a deed, etc) the matters referred to previously; the aforesaid; the foregoing\nthe introductory part of a grant, conveyance, etc\n(in the US) the part of a bill in equity that states the names of the parties, details of the plaintiff''s claims, etc\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('premium', '[p뤼미엄]\n보험료, 수수료, 사례금, 할증료\n상급의, 상질의, 고급의', 'payment / premium / subscription / repayment / deposit / instalment\nA premium is a sum of money that you pay regularly to an insurance company for an insurance policy.\nA premium is a sum of money that you have to pay for something in addition to the normal cost.\nPremium goods are of a higher than usual quality and are often expensive.\nIf something is at a premium, it is wanted or needed, but is difficult to get or achieve.\nIf you buy or sell something at a premium, you buy or sell it at a higher price than usual, for example because it is in short supply.\nIf you place a high premium on a quality or characteristic or put a high premium on it, you regard it as very important.\n', 0, '2016-09-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('preoccupy', '[p뤼아큐파-이]\n(생각, 걱정이) 뇌리를 사로잡다, 떠나지 않다', 'If something is preoccupying you, you are thinking about it a lot.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prep', '[p뤱]\n예비 학습(훈련)을 받다, 준비하다\n예습, 준비\n(일부 사립학교에서 방과 후에 하는) 자율 학습', 'If you prep something, you prepare it.\n', 0, '2016-09-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prepare', '[p뤼페어r]\n준비하다, 대비하다\n(약 등을) 제조하다', 'If you prepare something, you make it ready for something that is going to happen.\nIf you prepare for an event or action that will happen soon, you get yourself ready for it or make the necessary arrangements.\nWhen you prepare food, you get it ready to be eaten, for example by cooking it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('preposition', '[p뤠퍼지션]\n전치사', 'A preposition is a word such as ''by'', ''for'', ''into'', or ''with'' which usually has a noun group as its object.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prescribe', '[p뤼sk롸이v]\n처방하다, 처방을 내리다, 처방전을 쓰다\n규정하다, 제시/지시하다', 'If a doctor prescribes medicine or treatment for you, he or she tells you what medicine or treatment to have.\nIf a person or set of laws or rules prescribes an action or duty, they state that it must be carried out.\n', 0, '2016-09-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prescription', '[p^뤼sk륍션]\n처방전, 처방된 약, 처방\n(비유적으로) 처방/방안', 'A prescription is the piece of paper on which your doctor writes an order for medicine and which you give to a chemist or pharmacist to get the medicine.\nA prescription is a medicine which a doctor has told you to take.\nA prescription is a proposal or a plan which gives ideas about how to solve a problem or improve a situation.\nYou can take this prescription to the local pharmacist.\nI''m going to write you a prescription.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('present', '[p뤼^젠t]\n현재, 지금, 현시점, \n있는, 참석한, 존재하는\n선물\n선물하다, 제출하다, 인사/발표시키다\n(특히 공식적인 의식을 통해) 주다, 수여하다\n(사람들이 보거나 검토하도록) 제시/제출하다\n(특정한 방식으로) 보여주다, 나타내다, 묘사하다\n(문제 등을) 야기하다, 격게하다\n소개하다, 진행하다\n출석해 있는, 현재의, 현존하는', 'actual / current / present\nIf you present someone with something such as a prize or document, or if you present it to them, you formally give it to them.\nIf something presents a difficulty, challenge, or opportunity, it causes it or provides it.\nIf an opportunity or problem presents itself, it occurs, often when you do not expect it.\nWhen you present information, you give it to people in a formal way.\nIf you present someone or something in a particular way, you describe them in that way.\nThe way you present yourself is the way you speak and act when meeting new people.\nIf someone or something presents a particular appearance or image, that is how they appear or try to appear.\nIf you present yourself somewhere, you officially arrive there, for example for an appointment.\nIf someone presents a programme on television or radio, they introduce each item in it.\nYou use present to describe things and people that exist now, rather than those that existed in the past or those that may exist in the future.\nIn grammar, the present tenses of a verb are the ones that are used to talk about things that happen regularly or situations that exist at this time. The simple present tense uses the base form or the ''s'' form of a verb, as in ''I play tennis twice a week'' and ''He works in a bank''.\nThe present is the period of time that we are in now and the things that are happening now.\n"Allow me to present my knights," said King Arthur.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('present an appearance of', '~의인상을 주다, ~의 양상을 띠다', '', 0, '2016-09-26');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('present participle', '현재 분사', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('preservation', '보존, 보호, 보전, 방부', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('preserve', '[p뤼져r-v]\n(특정한 자질, 특색 등을) 보존하다, 보호하다, 지키다\n보존하는 것\n(채소를 소금, 식초에 절인) 저장 식품, 유전물', 'If you preserve a situation or condition, you make sure that it remains as it is, and does not change or end.\nIf you preserve something, you take action to save it or protect it from damage or decay.\nPreserves are foods such as jam that are made by cooking fruit with a large amount of sugar so that they can be stored for a long time.\nIf you say that a job or activity is the preserve of a particular person or group of people, you mean that they are the only ones who take part in it.\n', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('preserve for', '~위해 지키다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('preserve from ', '~으로부터 보호하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('preserver', '[p뤼저r버r]\n보호자, 수호자\n목재 방부제', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('president', '[p뤠지던t]\n대통령, 사장, 회장', 'The president of a country that has no king or queen is the person who is the head of state of that country.\nThe president of an organization is the person who has the highest position in it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('press', '~을 누르다, 압박하다\n언론, 기자, 보도', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('press for an answer', '대답을 강요하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('press for something', '~을 계속 요구하다', 'to make repeated and urgent requests for something\nThe president is pressed for an answer.\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('press on regardless', '한눈도 팔지 않고 일을 계속하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pressure', '[p뤠셔r]\n압력, 압박, 부담, 스트레스\n(대기의) 기압, (설득, 강요하기 위한) 압력\n압력을 가하다, 강요하다', 'pressure / stress / tension / strain\nPressure is force that you produce when you press hard on something.\nThe pressure in a place or container is the force produced by the quantity of gas or liquid in that place or container.\nIf there is pressure on a person, someone is trying to persuade or force them to do something.\nIf you are experiencing pressure, you feel that you must do a lot of tasks or make a lot of decisions in very little time, or that people expect a lot from you.\nIf you pressure someone to do something, you try forcefully to persuade them to do it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pretend', '[p뤼텐d]\n~인 체하다, 흉내내다, 가장하다\n~라고 가장하다, 상상하다\n가짜의', 'If you pretend that something is the case, you act in a way that is intended to make people believe that it is the case, although in fact it is not.\nIf children or adults pretend that they are doing something, they imagine that they are doing it, for example as part of a game.\nIf you do not pretend that something is the case, you do not claim that it is the case.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pretend to', '~인 체하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pretty', '[p뤼디]\n어느정도, 상당히, 꽤, 아주, 매우\n(매우 아름답지는 않지만) 매력적인, 예쁜, 귀여운 것\n귀여운\n', 'quite / fairly / rather / pretty\nbeautiful / pretty / handsome / attractive / lovely / good-looking / gorgeous\nIf you describe someone, especially a girl, as pretty, you mean that they look nice and are attractive in a delicate way.\nYou can use pretty before an adjective or adverb to mean ''quite'' or ''rather''.\n"Jack, look at those pretty fish with the teeth" said Annie.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pretty much', '꽤 많이, 거의', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pretty soon', '곧', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prevail', '[p뤼붸일]\n만연하다, 팽배하다, \n설득하다, 우세하다, 승리하다, 이기다', 'If a proposal, principle, or opinion prevails, it gains influence or is accepted, often after a struggle or argument.\nIf a situation, attitude, or custom prevails in a particular place at a particular time, it is normal or most common in that place at that time.\nIf one side in a battle, contest, or dispute prevails, it wins.\nIf you prevail upon someone to do something, you succeed in persuading them to do it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prevail against', '~을 압도하다, 이기다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prevail in a struggle', '투쟁에 이기다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prevent', '[p뤼^벤t]\n방지하다, 예방하다, 금지하다', 'To prevent something means to ensure that it does not happen.\nTo prevent someone from doing something means to make it impossible for them to do it.\nThere are many home appliances I use at home. First of all, probably the most important appliance is the fridge. It keeps food cold and prevents it from going bad.\n', 0, '2016-11-14');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prevent an accident', '사고를 방지하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prevent crime', '범죄를 예장하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('previous', '[p뤼비어s]\n이전의, 앞선, 먼저의, 예비의', 'A previous event or thing is one that happened or existed before the one that you are talking about.\nYou refer to the period of time or the thing immediately before the one that you are talking about as the previous one.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('previous engagement', '선약', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('previous notice', '사전 통고', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('price', '가격을 매기다\n값, 가격', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('price umbrella', '가격 보호', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pricey', '[^p롸이씨]\n값비싼', 'expensive / costly / overpriced / pricey / dear\nIf you say that something is pricey, you mean that it is expensive.\nThe problem is that dental braces are very pricey.\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prickle', '[p뤽끌]\n(살에 느껴지는 촉감이) 깔끄럽다, 까칠거리다\n따뜸거리다, \n(머리털이) 곤두서다, (몸이) 오싹하다\n(식물의 잎, 일부 동물의 피부에 있는 작은) 가시', 'If your skin prickles, it feels as if a lot of small sharp points are being stuck into it, either because of something touching it or because you feel a strong emotion.\nPrickles are small sharp points that stick out from leaves or from the stalks of plants.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pride', '자랑, 자부심, 자존심', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('priest', '[p뤼-st]\n(카톨릭의) 사제/신부\n(기독교 이외의) 성직자', 'A priest is a member of the Christian clergy in the Catholic, Anglican, or Orthodox church.\nIn many non-Christian religions a priest is a man who has particular duties and responsibilities in a place where people worship.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('primal chaos', '태초의 혼란상태', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('primarily', '[p롸이메럴릐]\n주로', 'You use primarily to say what is mainly true in a particular situation.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('primary', '제1의 것, 예비선거회\n제1의, 초기의, 근본적인, 주요한', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('primate', '[p롸이메잇t]\n영장류 (동물)', 'A primate is a member of the group of mammals which includes humans, monkeys, and apes.\nThe Primate of a particular country or region is the most important priest in that country or region.\n', 0, '2016-09-08');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prime minister', '총리, 수상, 국무 총리', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('primitive society', '원시 사회', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('principal', '교장\n주요한', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('principle', '[p륀시플]\n(개인의 도덕, 신념과 관련된) 원칙\n원리, 원칙, 법칙, 주의, 신조, 신념, 교리\n(물리, 자연의) 법칙', 'A principle is a general belief that you have about the way you should behave, which influences your behaviour.\nThe principles of a particular theory or philosophy are its basic rules or laws.\nScientific principles are general scientific laws which explain how something happens or works.\nIf you agree with something in principle, you agree in general terms to the idea of it, although you do yet know the details or know if it will be possible.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('print', '인쇄하다, 활자체로 쓰다\n인쇄, 인쇄물, 자취, 자국', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prior', '앞의, 전의, 기존의, 이제까지, 더 중요한', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prior commitment', '선약', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prior to A', 'A 이전에', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('priority', '[p롸이어러디]\n우선 사항, 우선권, 중요, 먼저, 사위, 우위', 'If something is a priority, it is the most important thing you have to do or deal with, or must be done or dealt with before everything else you have to do.\nIf you give priority to something or someone, you treat them as more important than anything or anyone else.\nIf something takes priority or has priority over other things, it is regarded as being more important than them and is dealt with first.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prison', '감옥, 교도소', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prisoner', '죄수, 포로, 수감자', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('private', '[^p롸이벳]\n사유의, (특정) 개인 소유의, (특정 개인, 집단) 전용의\n(개인의) 은밀한, 사생활의\n사병, 병사\n사적인, 개인의, 비밀의', 'Private industries and services are owned or controlled by an individual person or a commercial company, rather than by the state or an official organization.\nPrivate individuals are acting only for themselves, and are not representing any group, company, or organization.\nYour private things belong only to you, or may only be used by you.\nPrivate places or gatherings may be attended only by a particular group of people, rather than by the general public.\nPrivate meetings, discussions, and other activities involve only a small number of people, and very little information about them is given to other people.\nYour private life is that part of your life that is concerned with your personal relationships and activities, rather than with your work or business.\nYou can use private to describe situations or activities that are understood only by the people involved in them, and not by anyone else.\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('private door', '부엌문', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('privilege', '[p뤼빌릐쥐]\n특전(특혜), 특권, \n(어떤일을 하는 기회를 같는) 영광\n특권/특전/혜택을 주다', 'A privilege is a special right or advantage that only one person or group has.\nIf you talk about privilege, you are talking about the power and advantage that only a small group of people have, usually because of their wealth or their high social class.\nYou can use privilege in expressions such as be a privilege or have the privilege when you want to show your appreciation of someone or something or to show your respect.\nTo privilege someone or something means to treat them better or differently than other people or things rather than treat them all equally.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prize', '[p라이z]\n상, 상품, 경품, (성취하기 힘들지만) 소중한 것\n소중히하다, 평가하다\n상을 받을 만한', 'A prize is money or something valuable that is given to someone who has the best results in a competition or game, or as a reward for doing good work.\nYou can refer to someone or something as a prize when people consider them to be of great value or importance.\nYou use prize to describe things that are of such good quality that they win prizes or deserve to win prizes.\nSomething that is prized is wanted and admired because it is considered to be very valuable or very good quality.\nIf you prize something open or prize it away from a surface, you force it to open or force it to come away from the surface.\nIf you prize something such as information out of someone, you persuade them to tell you although they may be very unwilling to.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proactive', '[p로액디v]\n상황을 앞서서 주도하는, 주도적인, \n앞서서 대처하는, 사전 대책을 강구하는', 'Proactive actions are intended to cause changes, rather than just reacting to change.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('probable', '[p롸바붤]\n(어떤 일이) 있을것 같은, 개연성 있는\n(사람, 동물이) 우승할 것 같은 후보', 'If you say that something is probable, you mean that it is likely to be true or likely to happen.\nYou can use probable to describe a role or function that someone or something is likely to have.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('probable cost', '예상 비용', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('probable error', '확률 오차', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('probably', '[p^롸바블뤼]\n아마, 아마도', 'If you say that something is probably the case, you think that it is likely to be the case, although you are not sure.\nYou can use probably when you want to make your opinion sound less forceful or definite, so that you do not offend people.\n', 0, '2016-10-27');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('problem', '[p롸블럼]\n(다루거나 이해하기 힘든) 문제, 과제\n다루기 어려운\n문제를 일으키는', 'A problem is a situation that is unsatisfactory and causes difficulties for people.\nA problem is a puzzle that requires logical thought or mathematics to solve it.\nProblem children or problem families have serious problems or cause serious problems for other people.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('problematic', '[p러블러매릑]\n문제가 있는/많은,', 'Something that is problematic involves problems and difficulties.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proceed', '(이미 시작된 일을 계속) 진행하다\n계속해서/이어서 ~을 하다\n(특정 방향으로) 나아가다/이동하다', 'If you proceed to do something, you do it, often after doing something else first.\nIf you proceed with a course of action, you continue with it.\nIf an activity, process, or event proceeds, it goes on and does not stop.\nIf you proceed in a particular direction, you go in that direction.\nThe proceeds of an event or activity are the money that has been obtained from it.\nProceed onward with courage, and you will come out into the light."\n', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('process', '[p롸세s]\n(특정 결과를 달성하기 위한) 과정, 진행, 절차,\n처리, 공정\n(원자제, 식품 등을) 가공/처리 하다\n(문서, 요청 사항등을 공식적으로) 처리하다', 'A process is a series of actions which are carried out in order to achieve a particular result.\nA process is a series of things which happen naturally and result in a biological or chemical change.\nWhen raw materials or foods are processed, they are prepared in factories before they are used or sold.\nWhen people process information, they put it through a system or into a computer in order to deal with it.\nWhen people are processed by officials, their case is dealt with in stages and they pass from one stage of the process to the next.\nIf you are in the process of doing something, you have started to do it and are still doing it.\nIf you are doing something and you do something else in the process, you do the second thing as part of doing the first thing.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('process petroleum', '석유를 정제하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('procession', '[p러쎄션]\n(특히 의식의 일부로 하는) 행렬, 줄, 행진\n행렬을 지어 겉다, 줄지어 걷다', 'A procession is a group of people who are walking, riding, or driving in a line as part of a public event.\nMusicians played at the front and rear of the procession.\nThe funeral procession will leave the house at 7 am.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('procession a street', '거리를 행렬지어 걷다', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('processional', '[p러쎄셔널]\n(특정 종교적인) 행진에서 사용되는; 행렬의', 'Processional means used for or taking part in a ceremonial procession.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('procrastinate', '[p뤄k^뤄s티네잇t]\n(해야 할 일을 보통 하기가 싫어서) 미루다, 질질 끌다', 'If you procrastinate, you keep leaving things you should do until later, often because you do not want to do them.\nDon''t procrastinate your homework no longer!\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('produce', '[p러듀-s]\n(상품을 특히 대량으로) 생산하다, \n~을 생산하다, 만들어내다, (자식, 새끼를) 낳다\n(~에서) 꺼내 보이다, 보여 주다\n(도시, 국가 등이 사람을) 배출하다\n(영화, 영극 등을) 제작하다\n농산물, 수확물', 'make / create / develop / produce / generate / form\nTo produce something means to cause it to happen.\nIf you produce something, you make or create it.\nWhen things or people produce something, it comes from them or slowly forms from them, especially as the result of a biological or chemical process.\nIf you produce evidence or an argument, you show it or explain it to people in order to make them agree with you.\nIf you produce an object from somewhere, you show it or bring it out so that it can be seen.\nIf someone produces something such as a film, a magazine, or a CD, they organize it and decide how it should be done.\nProduce is food or other things that are grown in large quantities to be sold.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('product', '[p롸덕t]\n생산물, 상품, 제품, \n성과, 결과, (수학) 곱', 'product / goods / commodity / merchandise / produce / wares\nA product is something that is produced and sold in large quantities, often as a result of a manufacturing process.\nIf you say that someone or something is a product of a situation or process, you mean that the situation or process has had a significant effect in making them what they are.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('production', '[p러덕션]\n(식품, 상품, 자재의 특히 대량) 생산, 제작, 제품\n생산량, \n(자연스러운) 생성/분비\n(영화, 영극 등의) 제작', 'Production is the process of manufacturing or growing something in large quantities.\nProduction is the amount of goods manufactured or grown by a company or country.\nThe production of something is its creation as the result of a natural process.\nProduction is the process of organizing and preparing a play, film, programme, or CD, in order to present it to the public.\nA production is a play, opera, or other show that is performed in a theatre.\nWhen you can do something on production of or on the production of documents, you need to show someone those documents in order to be able to do that thing.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('productive', '[p러덕디v]\n(상품, 작물을 특히 대량으로) 생산/산출 하는, \n생산적인, 결실있는, ~을 야기하는 (불러일으키는)', 'Someone or something that is productive produces or does a lot for the amount of resources used.\nIf you say that a relationship between people is productive, you mean that a lot of good or useful things happen as a result of it.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('productive land', '비옥한 땅', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('productive society', '생산 조합', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profess', '[p로풰s]\n(특히 사실이 아닌 것을 사실이라고) 조장하다\n(신조, 감정 등을) 공언하다, 천명하다\n(특정 종교) 소속이다', 'If you profess to do or have something, you claim that you do it or have it, often when you do not.\nIf you profess a feeling, opinion, or belief, you express it.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profess ignorance', '모르는 체하다', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profess regret', '유감을 표하다', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profession', '[p러풰션]\n(특히 많은 교육이 필요한 전문적인) 직업, 직종, 직위\n(특정 직종) 종사자들, 전문직\n공언, 천명', 'work / employment / career / profession / occupation / trade\nA profession is a type of job that requires advanced education or training.\nYou can use profession to refer to all the people who have the same profession.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('professional', '[p러풰셔널]\n(특히 많은 교육이 필요한 전문적인) 직업의, 직종의, \n전문적인, 전문직이 종사하는, \n직업인, 전문가\n전문의, 프로의, 직업의\n전문직 종사자, 프로(선수), 전문가', 'Professional means relating to a person''s work, especially work that requires special training.\nProfessional people have jobs that require advanced education or training.\nYou use professional to describe people who do a particular thing to earn money rather than as a hobby.\nProfessional sports are played for money rather than as a hobby.\nIf you say that something that someone does or produces is professional, you approve of it because you think that it is of a very high standard.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('professor', '[p로^페써r]\n교수, 박사, 선생', 'A professor in a British university is the most senior teacher in a department.\nA professor in an American or Canadian university or college is a teacher of the highest rank.\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proficiency', '[p러퓌션씨]\n숙달, 능숙, 능란\n(시험에서 필수 과목을) 면제하다/되다', 'If you show proficiency in something, you show ability or skill at it.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proficient', '[p로퓌션t]\n능숙한, 능력', 'If you are proficient in something, you can do it well.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proficient at', '~에 능숙한', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proficient in', '~에 능숙한', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proficiently', '숙련되게, 능숙하게', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profile', '[f로퐈일]\n옆얼굴(의 윤곽), (얼굴의) 옆모습\n개요(서), 인지도, 윤관\n개요/프로필을 알려주다', 'Your profile is the outline of your face as it is seen when someone is looking at you from the side.\nIf you see someone in profile, you see them from the side.\nA profile of someone is a short article or programme in which their life and character are described.\nTo profile someone means to give an account of that person''s life and character.\nIf someone has a high profile, people notice them and what they do. If you keep a low profile, you avoid doing things that will make people notice you.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profiling', '[f로퐈일링]\n(개요 작성을 위한) 자료/정보 수집,\n프로파일링', 'the practice of categorizing people and predicting their behaviour according to particular characteristics such as race or age\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profit', '[p^롸핏t]\n(금전적인) 이익, 수익, 이윤, 순익, 수입\n이득, 이익,\n이익을 얻다, 득을 보다', 'A profit is an amount of money that you gain when you are paid more for something than it cost you to make, get, or do it.\nIf you profit from something, you earn a profit from it.\nIf you profit from something, or it profits you, you gain some advantage or benefit from it.\nSeller: I''m not making any profit at that price. How about $130?\n', 0, '2016-11-13');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profound', '[p뤄퐈운d]\n(영향, 느낌, 경험 등이) 엄청난/깊은\n(지식, 이해 등이) 깊은/심오한\n(질문 등이) 심오한/뜻 깊은\n극심한, 완전한', 'You use profound to emphasize that something is very great or intense.\nA profound idea, work, or person shows great intellectual depth and understanding.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profound sleep', '깊은 잠', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('profuse praise', '아낌없는 칭찬', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('programmatic', '계획/프로그램의, 계획에 따른', 'Programmatic ideas or policies follow a particular programme.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('programmatically', '계획/프로그램에 따라서', 'Now that the Internet has wormed its way into our everyday lives, and has become more of a necessity than a privilege, learning to programmatically send e-mails and allow users to communicate across the web is essential\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('progress', '[p롸g뤠s]\n진행, 진전, 진보, 발달, 향상\n진보/발전하다, 전진하다, (시간이) 지나다', 'Progress is the process of gradually improving or getting nearer to achieving or completing something.\nThe progress of a situation or action is the way in which it develops.\nTo progress means to move over a period of time to a stronger, more advanced, or more desirable state.\nIf events progress, they continue to happen gradually over a period of time.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('progress to something', '(~을 하다가 이어서 다른) ~으로 넘어가다/이동하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('progressive', '[p로g뤠시v]\n진보적인, \n점진적인, 꾸준히 진행하는\n(동사가) 진행형의', 'Someone who is progressive or has progressive ideas has modern ideas about how things should be done, rather than traditional ones.\nA progressive change happens gradually over a period of time.\nIn grammar, progressive means the same as continuous.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('progressive changes', '점진적 변화', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('progressive tax', '누진세', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('progressive view', '진보적인 견해', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prohibit', '[p러히빗t]\n(특히 법으로) 금지하다, 막다, 방해하다, 통제하다\n~하지 못하게 하다', 'If a law or someone in authority prohibits something, they forbid it or make it illegal.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prohibit by law', '법률로써 금지하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prohibit from', '~을 금지하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prohibit smoking', '흡연을 금지하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prohibition', '[p뤄히빗션]\n(특비 법에 의한) 금지, 금지법, 금지 규정\n금주법', 'A prohibition is a law or rule forbidding something.\nIn the United States, Prohibition was the law that prevented the manufacture, sale, and transporting of alcoholic drinks between 1919 and 1933. Prohibition also refers to the period when this law existed.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prohibition on discrimination', '차별 금지법', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('project', '[p뤄젝t]\n계획, 기획, 과제, 연구 프로젝트\n기획하다, 예상/추정하다, ', 'A project is a task that requires a lot of time and effort.\nA project is a detailed study of a subject by a pupil or student.\nIf something is projected, it is planned or expected.\nIf you project someone or something in a particular way, you try to make people see them in that way. If you project a particular feeling or quality, you show it in your behaviour.\nIf you project feelings or ideas on to other people, you imagine that they have the same ideas or feelings as you.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('project a missile', '(우주 공간으로) 미사일을 발사하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('project into', '~로 발사하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('project onto', '~로 투영/영사 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('promise', '[p^롸미s]\n~을 약속하다, ~을 기대하다\n~일 것 같다, ~의 조짐을 보이다\n약속, 전망, 장래성', 'If you promise that you will do something, you say to someone that you will definitely do it.\nIf you promise someone something, you tell them that you will definitely give it to them or make sure that they have it.\nIf a situation or event promises to have a particular quality or to be a particular thing, it shows signs that it will have that quality or be that thing.\nA promise is a statement which you make to a person in which you say that you will definitely do something or give them something.\nIf someone or something shows promise, they seem likely to be very good or successful.\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('promote', '[p로^모웃t]\n촉진하다, 고취하다\n홍보하다, \n승진/진급하다', 'If people promote something, they help or encourage it to happen, increase, or spread.\nIf a firm promotes a product, it tries to increase the sales or popularity of that product.\nIf someone is promoted, they are given a more important job or rank in the organization that they work for.\nIf a team that competes in a league is promoted, it starts competing in a higher division in the next season because it was one of the most successful teams in the lower division.\n', 0, '2016-11-09');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('promote the health benefits', '건강상의이점을 내세우다', 'Restaurants promote the health benefits of their dishes.\nThe doctor promoted the health benefits of the treatment.\nMy mom promotes the health benefits of eating at home.\n', 0, '2016-11-09');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('promotion', '승진, 승격, 홍모, 진흥, 판촉, 촉진', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prompt', '[p^럼ft]\n즉각적인, 지체 없는\n신속한, 시간을 엄수하는\n(사람에게 어떤 결정을 내리도록) 하다, 촉발하다\n(질문, 힌트 등을 주어 말을 하도록) 유도하다\n(배우가 대사를 잊었을 때) 대사를 상기시켜 주다\n정확히 (~시에), (~시) 정각에', 'To prompt someone to do something means to make them decide to do it.\nIf you prompt someone when they stop speaking, you encourage or help them to continue. If you prompt an actor, you tell them what their next line is when they have forgotten what comes next.\nA prompt action is done without any delay.\nIf you are prompt to do something, you do it without delay or you are not late.\n', 0, '2016-10-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prompt at', '즉시 ~ 하는', '', 0, '2016-10-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prompt reply', '즉답', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prone', '(좋지않은 일을) 당하기 쉬운, ~하기/당하기 쉬운', 'To be prone to something, usually something bad, means to have a tendency to be affected by it or to do it.\nIf you are lying prone, you are lying on your front.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prone to anger', '화내기 쉬운', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronoun', '대명사', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronounce', '[p러나운s]\n발음하다, \n(격식을 차려서) 표명/선언/선고 하다', 'To pronounce a word means to say it using particular sounds.\nIf you pronounce something to be true, you state that it is the case.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronounce after', '~을 따라서 발음하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronounce against somebody', '(판사가) ~에게 불리한 판결을 내리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronounce for somebody', '(판사가) ~에게 유리한 판결을 내리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronounce on something', '(의견, 결정을) 발표하다', 'to express an opinion or give a judgement on something\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronounced', '[p뤄나운st]\n뚜렷한, 현저한, 명백한, 단호한', 'Something that is pronounced is very noticeable.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronounced tendency', '뚜렷한 경향', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pronunciation', '[p러넌씨^에이션]\n(특정 단어, 소리의) 발음', 'The pronunciation of a word or language is the way in which it is pronounced.\n', 0, '2016-10-13');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proof', '[푸루-f]\n증거(물), 증명(서), 입증, 증거, 증명, 교정쇄\n~을 검사하다, ~을 점검하다, (천에) 방수처리하다,\n교정쇄를 만들다\n(손상 등에) 견딜 수 있는, 저항할 수 있는', 'Proof is a fact, argument, or piece of evidence which shows that something is definitely true or definitely exists.\nIn publishing, the proofs of a book, magazine, or article are a first copy of it that is printed so that mistakes can be corrected before more copies are printed and published.\nProof is used after a number of degrees or a percentage, when indicating the strength of a strong alcoholic drink such as whisky.\nHe needed more proof than that.\n', 0, '2016-09-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proof positive', '(~의) 확증', 'definite or convincing proof\n', 0, '2016-08-29');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proofread', '~을 교정보다, 교정하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prop', '[p뢉]\n받침, 지주, 버팀목, 받침대\n(영극, 영화에 쓰이는) 소품, \n받치다, 떠닫치다, ~을 기대 놓다', 'If you prop an object on or against something, you support it by putting something underneath it or by resting it somewhere.\nA prop is a stick or other object that you use to support something.\nTo be a prop for a system, institution, or person means to be the main thing that keeps them strong or helps them survive.\nThe props in a play or film are all the objects or pieces of furniture that are used in it.\nHe propped the pirate book in the sand.\nThey had all walked over to a row of wooden surfboards propped against the rocks.\n', 0, '2016-09-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propagate', '[p러퍼r게잇t]\n(사상, 신조, 정보를) 전파/선전하다\n전달하다, 전하다\n(동식물을) 번식시키다', 'If people propagate an idea or piece of information, they spread it and try to make people believe it or support it.\nIf you propagate plants, you grow more of them from the original ones.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propagate oneself', '번식하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propagation', '(동식물의) 번식, 증식\n(사상 등의) 선전, (관습 등의) 선전, 보급\n(소리 등의) 전파, 전달, (특질의) 유전', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propel', '[p러풸]\n(몰거나 밀거나 해서) ~을 나아가게 하다, \n추진시키다', 'To propel something in a particular direction means to cause it to move in that direction.\nIf something propels you into a particular activity, it causes you to do it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propensity', '경향, 성향, 기호', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propensity to consume', '(경제) 소비 경향', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proper', '[p롸퍼r]\n적절한, 올바른, 제대로, 제대로 된,\n엄밀한 의미의, 완전한, 고유의', 'You use proper to describe things that you consider to be real and satisfactory rather than inadequate in some way.\nThe proper thing is the one that is correct or most suitable.\nIf you say that a way of behaving is proper, you mean that it is considered socially acceptable and right.\nYou can add proper after a word to indicate that you are referring to the central and most important part of a place, event, or object and want to distinguish it from other things which are not regarded as being important or central to it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proper documentation', '적절한 증빙 서류', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('properly', '[p^롸뻐r뤼]\n제대로, 적절히\n(사회적, 도덕적으로) 올바로/제대로/예의 바르게\n실은, 사실', 'If something is done properly, it is done in a correct and satisfactory way.\nIf someone behaves properly, they behave in a way that is considered acceptable and not rude.\nB : I just don''t know how to dress up properly for clubbing.\n', 0, '2016-11-13');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('property', '[p^롸퍼디]\n재산, 소유, 소유물, \n토지, 땅, 부동산\n건물, 건물 구내, \n(사물의) 속성, 특징', 'building / property / premises / complex / structure / block / edifice\nSomeone''s property is all the things that belong to them or something that belongs to them.\nA property is a building and the land belonging to it.\nThe properties of a substance or object are the ways in which it behaves in particular conditions.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proportion', '[p로뽀r-션]\n(전체의) 부분, (전체에서 차지하는) 비율\n(다른것과 규모, 양 등을 대조하는) 비/비율\n크기, 규모, 비례', 'A proportion of a group or an amount is a part of it.\nThe proportion of one kind of person or thing in a group is the number of people or things of that kind compared to the total number of people or things in the group.\nThe proportion of one amount to another is the relationship between the two amounts in terms of how much there is of each thing.\nIf you refer to the proportions of something, you are referring to its size, usually when this is extremely large.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proportional', '[p로^포셔널]\n(~에) 비례하는', 'If one amount is proportional to another, the two amounts increase and decrease at the same rate so there is always the same relationship between them.\nSalary is proportional to years of experience.\n', 0, '2016-10-27');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propose', '[p러^포-우z]\n(계획, 생각 등을) 제안하다, 제의하다,\n(~을 하려고) 작정/의도하다\n청혼하다 프로포즈 하다\n(사람들이 고려해 보도록 가능한 설명 등을) 제시하다', 'If you propose something such as a plan or an idea, you suggest it for people to think about and decide upon.\nIf you propose to do something, you intend to do it.\nIf you propose a theory or an explanation, you state that it is possibly or probably true, because it fits in with the evidence that you have considered.\nIf you propose a motion for debate, or a candidate for election, you begin the debate or the election procedure by formally stating your support for that motion or candidate.\nIf you propose a toast to someone or something, you ask people to drink a toast to them.\nIf you propose to someone, or propose marriage to them, you ask them to marry you.\n', 0, '2016-09-26');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proposition', '[p롸^퍼지션]\n(특히 사업상의) 제의\n(하려는) 일, (처리해야 할) 문제, 과제\n(미국에서 국민투표를 위한) 법률 개정안\n명제, 진술', 'If you describe something such as a task or an activity as, for example, a difficult proposition or an attractive proposition, you mean that it is difficult or pleasant to do.\nA proposition is a statement or an idea which people can consider or discuss to decide whether it is true.\nIn the United States, a proposition is a question or statement about an issue of public policy which appears on a voting paper so that people can vote for or against it.\nA proposition is an offer or a suggestion that someone makes to you, usually concerning some work or business that you might be able to do together.\nIf someone who you do not know very well propositions you, they suggest that you have sex with them.\n', 0, '2016-11-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propound theory', '이론을 제기하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proprietary', '소유자\n소유자의, 소유의', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proprietary wealth', '소유 재산', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('propriety', '예의범절, 예절, 정당함, 타당성', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pros and cons', '장단점, 일장일단\n창반양론', 'the various arguments in favour of and against a motion, course of action, etc\nI thought abut the pros and cons.\nMake a list of the pros and cons.\nConsider the pros and cons before making a decision.\n', 0, '2016-11-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prosecute', '기소하다, 고소하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prosperous', '[p롸s퍼러s]\n번영한, 번창한', 'rich / wealthy / prosperous / affluent / well off / comfortable\nProsperous people, places, and economies are rich and successful.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prosperous years', '번영하는 시대', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prostitute', '매춘하다\n매춘부, 창녀', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('protect', '[p러^텍t]\n보호하다, 막다, 지키다\n(동물, 지역, 건물 등을 법으로) 보호하다, 보호법을 도입하다\n(보험으로) 보장하다', 'To protect someone or something means to prevent them from being harmed or damaged.\nIf an insurance policy protects you against an event such as death, injury, fire, or theft, the insurance company will give you or your family money if that event happens.\nBut should they fail to protect it, they would fade from life.\n', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('protégé', '(프) 피보호자, 부하, 제자', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('protein', '[p로우티-인]\n단백질', 'rotein is a substance found in food and drink such as meat, eggs, and milk. You need protein in order to grow and be healthy.\nYou need plenty of fruits and vegetables, small amounts of protein, and whole grains.\n', 0, '2016-09-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('protein nutrients', '단백질을 포함한 영양소', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('protend ignorance', '시치미 떼다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('protest', '항의하다, 이의를 제기하다\n시위, 항의, 저항, 데모', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proton', '양성자, 양자', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prototype', '원형, 시제품, 견본, 표준, 기본형', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proud', '[p롸우d]\n자랑스러운, 자랑스러워 하는, 자부심/자존심이 강한\n거만한, 오만한, 위품당당한', 'If you feel proud, you feel pleased about something good that you possess or have done, or about something good that a person close to you has done.\nYour proudest moments or achievements are the ones that you are most proud of.\nSomeone who is proud has respect for themselves and does not want to lose the respect that other people have for them.\nSomeone who is proud feels that they are better or more important than other people.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proud heritage', '자랑스러운 유산', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proudly', '[p롸웃릐]\n자랑스럽게, 위풍당당하게', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prove', '[^p루-v]\n입증하다, 증명하다, 밝혀지다\n~임이 드러나다/판명되다\n(자기 역량을) 입증해 보이다', 'If something proves to be true or to have a particular quality, it becomes clear after a period of time that it is true or has that quality.\nIf you prove that something is true, you show by means of argument or evidence that it is definitely true.\nIf you prove yourself to have a certain good quality, you show by your actions that you have it.\n', 0, '2016-10-28');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prove fatal', '치명상이 되다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prove one''s point', '누구의 말이 옳다는 것을 입증하다', 'You prove my point every time you''re late.\nJason: That proves my point.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prove out', '기대대로 되다, 결과가 만족스럽다, 성공하다\n~을 확인하다, ~을 철저히 조사하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prove true', '사실로 판명되다, 일치하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proverb', '[p롸-버rb]\n속담, 격언', 'A proverb is a short sentence that people often quote, which gives advice or tells you something about life.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proverb goes', '속담에 따르면 ~이다, \n~라는 속담이 있다', 'A proverb goes that time is money.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proverb runs', '속담에 따르면 ~이다, \n~라는 속담이 있다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provide', '[p러봐이d]\n제공하다, 지급하다, 준비하다\n규정하다', 'If you provide something that someone needs or wants, or if you provide them with it, you give it to them or make it available to them.\nIf a law or agreement provides that something will happen, it states that it will happen.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provide against something', '~에 대비하다', 'to make plans in order to deal with or prevent a bad or unpleasant situation\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provide for somebody', '~를 부양하다', 'to give somebody the things that they need to live, such as food, money and clothing\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provide for something', '~에 대해 준비/대비하다\n(법률, 규칙 등이) ~을 가능하게 하다, 허용하다', 'to make plans or arrangements to deal with something that may happen in the future\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('providence', '[p롸비던s]\n(신의) 섭리', 'luck / chance / coincidence / accident / fortune / fate / destiny / providence\nProvidence is God, or a force which is believed by some people to arrange the things that happen to us.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provision', '[p러뷔젼]\n지급, 제공, 대비, 준비, 규정', 'The provision of something is the act of giving it or making it available to people who need or want it.\nIf you make provision for something that might happen or that might need to be done, you make arrangements to deal with it.\nIf you make provision for someone, you support them financially and make sure that they have the things that they need.\nA provision in a law or an agreement is an arrangement which is included in it.\nProvisions are supplies of food.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provisory clause', '단서', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provoke', '[p로보욱k]\n(특정한 반응을) 유발하다\n화나게/짜증나게 하다. 도발하다', 'If you provoke someone, you deliberately annoy them and try to make them behave aggressively.\nIf something provokes a reaction, it causes it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provoke a laugh', '욱게 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provoke a riot', '폭동을 선동하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provoke debate', '논쟁을 야기하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provoke into', '자극해서 ~하게 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('provoke mirth', '흥겨움을 자아내다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prow', '[p롸우]\n이물, 뱃머리\n용맹스러운, 용감한', 'The prow of a ship or boat is the front part of it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proximity', '[p락시미디]\n(거리 시간상으로) 가까움, 근접,', 'Proximity to a place or person is nearness to that place or person.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proximity of blood', '근친', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proximity to', '~에 가까움', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('proxy', '[p롹씨]\n대리, 대리인, 대리권', 'If you do something by proxy, you arrange for someone else to do it for you.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prune', '[p루운]\n말린 자두, 짙은 적자색\n(가지,뿌리를) 잘라내다, (나무를) 전지하다', 'A prune is a dried plum.\nWhen you prune a tree or bush, you cut off some of the branches so that it will grow better the next year.\nIf you prune something, you cut out all the parts that you do not need.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('prune away', '잘라내다 \n(불필요한 것을) 제거하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('PS', 'postscript\n추신', 'You write PS to introduce something that you add at the end of a letter after you have signed it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('psychiatrist', '[싸이카이어튜뤼st]\n정신과의사', 'A psychiatrist is a doctor who treats people suffering from mental illness.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('psychology', '[싸이컬러쥐]\n심리학, 심리, 심리작용', 'Psychology is the scientific study of the human mind and the reasons for people''s behaviour.\nThe psychology of a person is the kind of mind that they have, which makes them think or behave in the way that they do.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('public', '[파블뤽]\n일반사람들, 대중, \n대중을 위한, 공공의, 공개의, 대중적으로 알려진, ', 'You can refer to people in general, or to all the people in a particular country or community, as the public.\nYou can refer to a set of people in a country who share a common interest, activity, or characteristic as a particular kind of public.\nPublic means relating to all the people in a country or community.\nPublic means relating to the government or state, or things that are done for the people by the state.\nPublic buildings and services are provided for everyone to use.\nA public place is one where people can go about freely and where you can easily be seen and heard.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('public awareness', '대중의 의식/관심', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('public body', '공공단체', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('public debate', '공개 토론회', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('public disorder', '대중들의 시위', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('public institution', '공공 기관', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('publicity', '[퍼블뤼시디]\n매스컴의 관심, 언론의 주목, 널리 알려짐\n명성, 평판\n홍보/광고업, 선전', 'Publicity is information or actions that are intended to attract the public''s attention to someone or something.\nWhen the news media and the public show a lot of interest in something, you can say that it is receiving publicity.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('publicity for', '~의 주목', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('publish', '[파블뤼시]\n출판/발행하다, 발표/공개/출판하다', 'When a company publishes a book or magazine, it prints copies of it, which are sent to shops to be sold.\nWhen the people in charge of a newspaper or magazine publish a piece of writing or a photograph, they print it in their newspaper or magazine.\nIf someone publishes a book or an article that they have written, they arrange to have it published.\nIf you publish information or an opinion, you make it known to the public by having it printed in a newspaper, magazine, or official document.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puck', '[^퍽]\n퍽(아이스하키에서 공처럼 치는 고무 원반)', 'In the game of ice hockey, the puck is the small rubber disc that is used instead of a ball.\n', 0, '2016-10-25');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puddle', '[파들]\n(특히 비온뒤의) 물웅덩이, 액체가 괸 것\n물웅덩이를 만들다, (물을) 흐리게 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pudgy', '통통한, 땅달막한', 'If you describe someone as pudgy, you mean that they are rather fat in an unattractive way.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puff', '[파-f]\n(담배, 파이프 등을) 뻐끔뻐끔 피우다,\n(많은 양의 연기/김을) 내뿜다, 뿜어져 나오다 \n숨을 내뿜다, 씩씩거리다, 부풀다\n(담배, 파이프 등을 뻐끔뻐끔) 피우기, 빨기\n숨, 호흡', 'If someone puffs at a cigarette, cigar, or pipe, they smoke it.\nIf you puff smoke or moisture from your mouth or if it puffs from your mouth, you breathe it out.\nIf an engine, chimney, or boiler puffs smoke or steam, clouds of smoke or steam come out of it.\nIf you are puffing, you are breathing loudly and quickly with your mouth open because you are out of breath after a lot of physical effort.\nA puff of something such as air or smoke is a small amount of it that is blown out from somewhere.\nPuffs of frosty air blew from the stag''s nostrils.\nHe blew out a puff of air, then broke into a leaping run.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puff at', '~을 피우다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puff on', '~을 피우다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puff something out', '(특히 공기를 채워) ~을 불룩하게 부풀리다', 'to make something larger and rounder by filling it with air\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puff up', '부어오르다', 'to swell or to make something swell and increase in size\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puffy', '[퍼r퓌]\n부어있는(것 같은)\n뭉게뭉게/두둥실 피어 오른', 'If a part of someone''s body, especially their face, is puffy, it has a round, swollen appearance.\nPuffy snow clouds were moving in.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull', '[풀]\n당기다, 끌다, 철수시키다, \n(없애거나 치우기위해) 뽑다, 빼다, 잡아당기다\n(특정 방향으로) 당기다\n(배, 보트의) 노를 젓다\n당기기, 끌기, 잡아당기기', 'injure / wound / hurt / bruise / maim / sprain / pull / twist / strain\nWhen you pull something, you hold it firmly and use force in order to move it towards you or away from its previous position.\nWhen you pull an object from a bag, pocket, or cupboard, you put your hand in and bring the object out.\nWhen a vehicle, animal, or person pulls a cart or piece of machinery, they are attached to it or hold it, so that it moves along behind them when they move forward.\nIf you pull yourself or pull a part of your body in a particular direction, you move your body or a part of your body with effort or force.\nWhen a driver or vehicle pulls to a stop or a halt, the vehicle stops.\nBoka and Kama pulled themselves onto their boards.\n', 0, '2016-09-19');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull alongside of', '~과 나란히 나아가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull an oar', '노를 젓다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull apart', '그것을 잡아 찢다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull away', '움직이기 시작하다, 떠나다', 'when a vehicle pulls away, it begins to move\nto gradually move further in front of somebody/something; to start to win a game or competition by getting more points than your opponent\n(from somebody/something) to move quickly away from somebody/something\nJust before the tsunami strikes, water may pull away from the shore.\nShe pulled away from the circle and tumbled back into the grass.\n', 0, '2016-09-30');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull back', '(군대가) 후퇴하다, 물러나다\n(하려던 일을) 취소하다', 'to move back from a place; to make an army move back from a place\n(from somebody/something) to move backwards away from somebody/something\nto decide not to do something you were intending to do, usually because of possible problems\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull it apart', '떼어 놓다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull off', '~을 벗기다, 벗다,\n(도로 밖으로) ~을 빼다', 'The ninjas pulled iron bands off their hands.\nHe pulled off his shoes and stockings and joined Annie.\nHe pulled off his wreath of red fluffy flowers.\nWithout a word, the knight pulled off his red cloak.\n', 0, '2016-09-28');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull on', '머리부터 뒤집어써 입거나 잡아당겨 착용하는\n입다. 신다', 'He pulled on his jeans and sneakers and a sweatshirt.\nHe and Annie pulled on white gloves.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull out', '~을 꺼내다, ~을 빼내다, \n철수하다, 벗어나다, 빼다, 손을 떼다\n옆으로 빠져나오다\n철수하다, 빼다, 벗어나다, 뽑다', 'if a train or bus pulls out, it leaves a place\nto move away from the side of a road, from behind something, etc.\nboss\nHis hands trembled as he pulled out his notebook and pencil.\n', 0, '2016-10-14');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull out of', '~에서 철수하다', 'to move or to make somebody/something move away from something or stop being involved in it\n( pull out of doing something) to stop being involved in something or decide not to do something you had promised to do; to make somebody do this\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull over', '차를 길가로 붙이다, 길 한쪽에 세우다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull something apart', '~을 (여러 부분으로) 뜯어내다', 'to destroy something or separate something into pieces by pulling parts of it in different directions\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull up', '(차 등이) 서다, (사람이) 차를 세우다\n~을 잡아 당기다, 끌어 올리다\n(의자 등을) 다른 사람 옆으로 바싹 대다', 'Please pull up your shirt so I can listen to your chest.\nPull up and parallel park in between those two cars there.\nPull up the chairs here, please.\nArthur climbed into bed and pulled up the covers.\n', 0, '2016-11-20');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pull up a weed', '잡초를 뽑다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pulse', '[펄s]\n맥박치다, 맥동하다\n맥박, 파동, 맥동', 'Your pulse is the regular beating of blood through your body, which you can feel when you touch particular parts of your body, especially your wrist.\nIn music, a pulse is a regular beat, which is often produced by a drum.\nA pulse of electrical current, light, or sound is a temporary increase in its level.\nIf you refer to the pulse of a group in society, you mean the ideas, opinions, or feelings they have at a particular time.\nIf something pulses, it moves, appears, or makes a sound with a strong regular rhythm.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pumice', '[파마s]\n부석, 속돌', 'Pumice is a kind of grey stone from a volcano and is very light in weight. It can be rubbed over surfaces, especially your skin, that you want to clean or make smoother.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pump', '[^펌p]\n펌프, \n(물, 공기 등을 펌프로) 퍼 올리다, 퍼내다\n(거세게) 솟구치다, 쏟아지다\n(아래위, 안팎으로 빠르게) 흔들다, 움직이다\n질문을 퍼붓다', 'A pump is a machine or device that is used to force a liquid or gas to flow in a particular direction.\nA petrol or gas pump is a machine with a tube attached to it that you use to fill a car with petrol.\nPumps are canvas shoes with flat rubber soles which people wear for sports and leisure.\nPumps are women''s shoes that do not cover the top part of the foot and are usually made of plain leather.\nTo pump a liquid or gas in a particular direction means to force it to flow in that direction using a pump.\nIf someone has their stomach pumped, doctors remove the contents of their stomach, for example because they have swallowed poison or drugs.\nIf you pump money or other resources into something such as a project or an industry, you invest a lot of money or resources in it.\nIf you pump someone about something, you keep asking them questions in order to get information.\n', 0, '2016-11-22');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pump something up', '(펌프로 공기 등을) 주입하다, 채워 넣다\n(양, 가치 등을) 인상하다, 증가시키다', 'to fill a tyre, etc. with air using a pump\nto increase the amount, value or volume of something\n', 0, '2016-11-22');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pumpkin', '[^펌퀸]\n호박', 'A pumpkin is a large, round, orange vegetable with a thick skin.\n', 0, '2016-09-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punch', '[펀취]\n주먹으로 치다, 구멍을 뚫다, \n~을 치다, 구멍을내다\n펀치, 주먹질, 박력, 효과', 'If you punch someone or something, you hit them hard with your fist.\nIf you punch the air, you put one or both of your fists forcefully above your shoulders as a gesture of delight or victory.\nIf you punch something such as the buttons on a keyboard, you touch them in order to store information on a machine such as a computer or to give the machine a command to do something.\nIf you punch holes in something, you make holes in it by pushing or pressing it with something sharp.\nA punch is a tool that you use for making holes in something.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punch something in', '(컴퓨터 자판 같은 것을 쳐서)\n(~ 안에) ~을 입력하다/쳐 넣다 ', 'to put information into a computer, etc. by pressing keys\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punctual', '[펑슈얼]\n시간을 지키는/엄수하는', 'If you are punctual, you do something or arrive somewhere at the right time and are not late.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punctual in', '정확히 ~ 하는', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punctual payment', '기한대로의 지불', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punctuation', '[펑츄에이션]\n구두법, 구두점', 'Punctuation is the use of symbols such as full stops or periods, commas, or question marks to divide written words into sentences and clauses.\nPunctuation is the symbols that you use to divide written words into sentences and clauses.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puncture', '[^펑처r]\n(타이어에 난) 펑크\n(뾰족한 것에 찔려서 생긴) 구멍, 상처\n펑크/구멍를 내다, 펑크/구멍가 나다\n(자신감, 자존심 등이 갑자기) 없어지게/상하게 만들다', 'A puncture is a small hole in a car tyre or bicycle tyre that has been made by a sharp object.\nA puncture is a small hole in someone''s skin that has been made by or with a sharp object.\nIf a sharp object punctures something, it makes a hole in it.\nIf a car tyre or bicycle tyre punctures or if something punctures it, a hole is made in the tyre.\nIf someone''s feelings or beliefs are punctured, their feelings or beliefs are made to seem wrong or foolish, especially when this makes the person feel disappointed or upset.\n', 0, '2016-11-22');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pungent sauce', '매운 소스', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punish', '[^퍼니쉬]\n처벌하다, 벌을주다, 혼내다', 'To punish someone means to make them suffer in some way because they have done something wrong.\nTo punish a crime means to punish anyone who commits that crime.\n', 0, '2016-10-08');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punish for', '~때문에 벌주다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('punitive provision', '벌칙', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puny', '[퓨니]\n작고 연약한, 왜소한, 아주 작은, 연약한', 'Someone or something that is puny is very small or weak.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pupil', '[퓨-펄]\n(특히 어린) 학생, 문하생/제자, 눈동자, 동공', 'student / pupil / schoolboy / schoolchild / schoolgirl\nThe pupils of a school are the children who go to it.\nA pupil of a painter, musician, or other expert is someone who studies under that expert and learns his or her skills.\nThe pupils of your eyes are the small, round, black holes in the centre of them.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puppet', '[파펫t]\n(인형극에 쓰이는) 인형, 꼭두각시,', 'A puppet is a doll that you can move, either by pulling strings which are attached to it or by putting your hand inside its body and moving your fingers.\nYou can refer to a person or country as a puppet when you mean that their actions are controlled by a more powerful person or government, even though they may appear to be independent.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puppet government', '괴뢰정부', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puppet show', '인형극', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puppy', '[팝비]\n강아지', 'A puppy is a young dog.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purchase', '[^퍼r-처s]\n구입, 구매, 매입, \n구입하다, 구매하다, 인수하다, 사다', 'When you purchase something, you buy it.\nThe purchase of something is the act of buying it.\nA purchase is something that you buy.\nIf you get a purchase on something, you manage to get a firm grip on it.\nA : I would like to purchase some meat.\nB : Yes. Here you are. Would you like to purchase it?\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purchase for', '~때문에 구매하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purchase value', '매입 가격', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pure', '[퓨어r]\n(다른것이 석이지 않은) 순수한, 순전한, 완전한, \n흠이없는', 'A pure substance is not mixed with anything else.\nSomething that is pure is clean and does not contain any harmful substances.\nIf you describe something such as a colour, a sound, or a type of light as pure, you mean that it is very clear and represents a perfect example of its type.\nIf you describe a form of art or a philosophy as pure, you mean that it is produced or practised according to a standard or form that is expected of it.\nPure science or pure research is concerned only with theory and not with how this theory can be used in practical ways.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pure and simple', '(명사 뒤에서 그 의미를 강조하여) 다름 아닌/그야말로', 'and nothing else\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pure gold', '순금', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pure voice', '더없이 청아한 목소리', '', 0, '2016-09-28');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purifier', '[퓨러퐈이어r]\n정화장치, 정화기', 'A purifier is a device or a substance that is used to purify something such as water, air, or blood.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purple', '[^퍼r쁠]\n자주색의\n미사여구로된 글', 'Something that is purple is of a reddish-blue colour.\nPurple prose or a purple patch is a piece of writing that contains very elaborate language or images.\nOn a hillside beyond the meadow, red and purple flowers sparkled like bright buttons.\n', 0, '2016-09-29');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purpose', '[퍼r-퍼s]\n(이루고자 하는) 목적, 목표, \n(특정 상황에서 무엇을) 하기 위함, 용도, 의도,\n결심하다', 'purpose / aim / intention / plan / point / idea\nThe purpose of something is the reason for which it is made or done.\nYour purpose is the thing that you want to achieve.\nPurpose is the feeling of having a definite aim and of being determined to achieve it.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purposely', '[퍼r퍼슬뤼]\n고의로, 일부러', 'If you do something purposely, you do it intentionally.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purposely refrain from', '생각이 있어 ~을 삼가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purr', '[퍼r-어]\n(고양이가 특히 기분이 좋아서) 가르랑거리다\n(계속해서 낮게) 부웅부웅/부르릉 하는 소리를 내다', 'When a cat purrs, it makes a low vibrating sound with its throat because it is contented.\nWhen the engine of a machine such as a car purrs, it is working and making a quiet, continuous, vibrating sound.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('purse', '[^퍼r-s]\n(특히 여성용의 작은) 지갑, 핸드백, 가방\n(입, 입술을) 오므리다, 꽉 다물다\n', 'A purse is a very small bag that people, especially women, keep their money in.\nA purse is a small bag that women carry.\nPurse is used to refer to the total amount of money that a country, family, or group has.\nIf you purse your lips, you move them into a small, rounded shape, usually because you disapprove of something or when you are thinking.\n', 0, '2016-11-08');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pursue', '[퍼r쑤우]\n추적하다, 쫓다, 추진하다, \n(논의, 조사, 관여 등을)계속하다\n(붙잡기 위해) 뒤쫓다/추격하다', 'If you pursue an activity, interest, or plan, you carry it out or follow it.\nIf you pursue a particular aim or result, you make efforts to achieve it, often over a long period of time.\nIf you pursue a particular topic, you try to find out more about it by asking questions.\nIf you pursue a person, vehicle, or animal, you follow them, usually in order to catch them.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pursue a hobby', '취미를 추구하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pursue a line', '방침을 따르다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pursue an aim', '계획대로 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pursue pleasure', '쾌락을 추구하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('push', '밀다, 노력하다, 누르다, 강요하다\n밀기, 끈기, 박력, 설득, 노력, 대공격', '\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('push forward', '(특히 장거리, 힘든 길을) 계속 나아가다', 'to move forward through a group of people until you are near the front\nif soldiers, an army, etc. push forward, they move forward against the enemy, especially with some difficulty\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pushy', '억지가 쎈, 밀어붙이는, 뻔뻔스러운', 'If you describe someone as pushy, you mean that they try in a forceful way to get things done as they would like or to increase their status or influence.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put', '[풋]\n(특별한 장소, 위치에) 넣다, 놓다\n(사물을 억지로) 밀어/집어 넣다\n부탁하다, 붙이다, 달다\n(어떤 상태, 조건 등에) 처하게 하다', 'put - put - put\nWhen you put something in a particular place or position, you move it into that place or position.\nIf you put someone somewhere, you cause them to go there and to stay there for a period of time.\nTo put someone or something in a particular state or situation means to cause them to be in that state or situation.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put a dent in', '~을 움푹 들어가게 하다, ~을 줄이다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put a halt to', '(권위로) 멈추가 하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put a polish on', '~의 광을 내다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put an end to', '~을 끝내다, 그만두게 하다\n(악습 따위)를 없애다, 폐지하다\n(동물 따위)를 죽이다', 'My mother put an end to my father smoking in the house. He has to smoke outside now.\nPaul: I guess you put an end to that.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put aside for', '~을 위해 따로 남겨두다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put down', '~을 받아 적다, ~을 아래에 놓다,\n~을 진압하다', 'if a plane or its pilot puts down, the plane comes down to the ground\n', 0, '2016-10-17');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put in cold storage', '무기한 연기하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put money away', '저축하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put off', '~(계획)을 연기하다, 미루다, \n~을 벗다, 버리다, 기세를 꺽다', 'He puts off going to the dentist.\nHis mother sighed. "putting off bad news doesn''t make it get any better. And sometimes it makes it worse. Besides, Dad and I can''t help you with a problem if we don''t know you have one."\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put on', '입다, 쓰다, 바르다, 신다, ~인 체 하다, ~을 늘리다, 더하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put on weight', '체중이 늘다, 살이찌다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put out', '(불 등을) 끄다, 내밀다, 뻡다, (힘을) 내다, 발휘하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put over a shutter', '셔터를 내리다', '', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put sauce on', '~에 소스를 뿌리다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put somebody in charge of something', '~에게 ~에 대한 책임을 맞기다', 'She put me in charge of dinner because she''s not feeling well today.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something aside', '(보통 감정, 의견 차이 등을) 무시하다, 제쳐놓다\n(나중에 쓸 수 있도록) ~을 따로 때어 놓다', 'to place something to one side\nto keep an item for a customer to collect later\nto save some money to use later\nto decide to keep a period of time for a particular task or activity\nto ignore or forget something\nHe put aside his tray.\n', 0, '2016-10-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something away', '(다 쓰고난 물건을 보관 장소에) 넣다/치우다\n(돈을) 모으다, 저축하다\n(많은 음식, 술 등을) 먹어 치우다, 마셔 버리다', 'to put something in a box, drawer, etc. because you have finished using it\n(informal) to eat or drink large quantities of something\nto score a goal\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something back', '~을 다시 제자리에 갖다 놓다\n(시간, 날짜를) 연기하다, 미루다\n~을 지체/지연 하다\n시계 바늘을 뒤로 돌려 맞추다', 'to return something to its usual place; to return something to the place it was before\nto move something to a later time or date\nto cause something to be delayed\nto move the hands of a clock back to give the correct earlier time, especially at the end of summer\nto drink a large quantity of alcohol\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something forward', '(시간, 날짜를) 앞당기다\n(시계 바늘을) 앞당겨 맟추다\n(안건, 의견을) 내다, 제기하다', 'to move something to an earlier time or date\nto move the hands of a clock forward to give the correct time, especially at the beginning of summer\n(put something forth) to suggest an idea or a plan so that it can be discussed\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something in', '(장비, 가구를) 들여놓다/설치하다\n(편지, 이야기 등의 속에) ~을 집어넣다/포함시키다\n(주요 주장 등을) 제기/제출하다\n(많은 시간, 노력을) 쏟다, 들이다', 'to include something in a story, a letter, etc.\nto pay money into a bank account\nto fit a piece of equipment, furniture, etc. into a particular place\nto give something, such as time or money, in order to help somebody/something\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something off', '(시간, 날짜를) 미루다, 연기하다', '(put off doing something) to change something to a later date or time\nto switch something off\nTracey: I''ve been putting this off because I thought this place is always busy.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something on', '~을 입다/쓰다/끼다/걸치다\n(얼굴, 피부에) ~을 바르다\n(기구 등을) 가동/작동 시키다', 'to put an item of clothing, etc. on your body\nto apply something to your skin\nto begin to cook food\nto grow heavier by the amount mentioned\nto provide something specially\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put something together', '(부품을) 조립하다, (이것저것을 모아) 만들다, 준비하다', 'build / construct / assemble / erect / set up / put up / put together\nto make or repair something by fitting parts together\nto create something\nto combine things\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put together', '합하다', 'used when comparing or contrasting somebody/something with a group of other people or things to mean ‘combined'' or ‘in total''\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put up a pole', '기둥을 세우다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put up an umbrella', '우산을 쓰다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('put up with', '~을 참다\n(짜증스럽거나 불쾌한 것을 불평 없이) 참다, 받아들이다', 'to accept somebody/something that is annoying or unpleasant without complaining\nA : And he has to put up with a cast on his leg for 3 weeks.\n', 0, '2016-10-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puzzle', '[^퍼즐]\n당황하게 하다, 어리둥절하게 만들다\n퍼즐, 당황, \n(이해, 설명하기 힘든) 수수깨끼/미스터리', 'If something puzzles you, you do not understand it and feel confused.\nIf you puzzle over something, you try hard to think of the answer to it or the explanation for it.\nA puzzle is a question, game, or toy which you have to think about carefully in order to answer it correctly or put it together properly\nYou can describe a person or thing that is hard to understand as a puzzle.\n', 0, '2016-09-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puzzle over', '~을 숙고하다, ~에 머리를 썩히다', 'to think hard about something because you want to understand it\n', 0, '2016-09-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puzzle over a problem', '문제를 해결하려고 머리를 짜내다', '', 0, '2016-09-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('puzzle something out', '골똘히 생각하여 ~을 알아내다, \n~에 대한 답을 찾다', 'to find the solution to a difficult problem by thinking carefully about it\n', 0, '2016-09-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('pyramid', '[퓌러미-d]\n(고대 이집트의) 피라미드', 'Pyramids are ancient stone buildings with four triangular sloping sides. The most famous pyramids are those built in ancient Egypt to contain the bodies of their kings and queens.\nA pyramid is a shape, object, or pile of things with a flat base and sloping triangular sides that meet at a point.\nYou can describe something as a pyramid when it is organized so that there are fewer people at each level as you go towards the top.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quack', '엉터리 치료를 하다\n돌팔이 의사, 허풍선이\n(약, 치료가) 엉터리인\n(오리가) 꽥꽥 우는 소리', 'If you call someone a quack or a quack doctor, you mean that they claim to be skilled in medicine but are not.\nQuack remedies or quack cures are medical treatments that you think are unlikely to work because they are not scientific.\nWhen a duck quacks, it makes the noise that ducks typically make.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quad', '사각현의 안뜰', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quake', '[k^웨익k]\n(공포, 긴장감으로) 몸을 떨다, 전율하다, \n흔들리다, 진동하다', 'A quake is the same as an earthquake.\nIf you quake, you shake, usually because you are very afraid.\nIf you are quaking in your boots or quaking in your shoes, you feel very nervous or afraid, and may be feeling slightly weak as a result.\nNew Zealand''s 7.8 magnitude quake ripped this mountain apart by 10 metres.\n', 0, '2016-11-24');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('qualification', '[퀄뤼피케이션]\n(필요한 교육, 시험 등을 거처서 얻게되는) 자격/자격증\n자질, 능력, 자격, 자격 증명서\n단서, 조건', 'Your qualifications are the examinations that you have passed.\nQualification is the act of passing the examinations you need to work in a particular profession.\nThe qualifications you need for an activity or task are the qualities and skills that you need to be able to do it.\nA qualification is a detail or explanation that you add to a statement to make it less strong or less general.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quality', '품질, (사람의)자질, 특성, 속성, 재능\n양질의, 고급의', 'The quality of something is how good or bad it is.\nSomething of quality is of a high standard.\nSomeone''s qualities are the good characteristics that they have which are part of their nature.\nYou can describe a particular characteristic of a person or thing as a quality.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quantifier', '수량사, 수량 형용사', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quantify', '~을 정량화하다, 양을 재다, 분량을 정하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quantity', '[콴터디]\n(특정의, 불특정의 상당한) 양, 수량, 분량, 액수\n다량, 다수', 'A quantity is an amount that you can measure or count.\nThings that are produced or available in quantity are produced or available in large amounts.\nYou can use quantity to refer to the amount of something that there is, especially when you want to contrast it with its quality.\nIf you say that someone or something is an unknown quantity, you mean that not much is known about what they are like or how they will behave.\n', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quantity production', '대량 생산', '', 0, '2016-09-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quantum', '[퀀-텀]\n양자', 'In physics, quantum theory and quantum mechanics are concerned with the behaviour of atomic particles.\nA quantum leap or quantum jump in something is a very great and sudden increase in its size, amount, or quality.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quarrel', '싸우다, 말다툼하다\n말다툼', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quarrel hammer and tongs', '격렬하게 싸우다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quarter', '[^쿼러r]\n1/4, 분기, 15분, 25 센트 동전, \n~을 4등분하다, 숙박하다\n', 'half / whole / quarter\nA quarter is one of four equal parts of something.\nA quarter is a fixed period of three months. Companies often divide their financial year into four quarters.\nWhen you are telling the time, you use quarter to talk about the fifteen minutes before or after an hour. For example, 8.15 is quarter past eight, and 8.45 is quarter to nine. In American English, you can also say that 8.15 is a quarter after eight and 8.45 is a quarter of nine.\nA quarter is an American or Canadian coin that is worth 25 cents.\nIf you quarter something such as a fruit or a vegetable, you cut it into four roughly equal parts.\nIf the number or size of something is quartered, it is reduced to about a quarter of its previous number or size.\nIf you do something at close quarters, you do it very near to a particular person or thing.\n', 0, '2016-11-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('queer transaction', '부정 거래', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quest', '[^쿠웨st]\n탐구, 탐색\n탐구/탐색하다', 'A quest is a long and difficult search for something.\nThey told him he must send his knights on a quest to the Otherworld, to recapture our kingdom''s joy.\nHe held a staff and wore a flowing red cloak-the same cloak Jack and Annie had worn on their quest.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('question', '질문하다, 묻다, ~을 조사하다\n질문, 물음, 문제, 의문', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('queue', '줄에 서다, 머리를 땋아 늘이다\n(차례를 기다리는) 줄, 대기 행렬', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quick', '[^쿠윅]\n(속도상으로, 걸리는 시간이 짧아서) 빠른, 신속한, \n즉각적인, 지체 없는\n재빨리, 신속하게', 'quick / quickly / fast\nSomeone or something that is quick moves or does things with great speed.\nSomething that is quick takes or lasts only a short time.\nQuick means happening without delay or with very little delay.\nIf you are quick to do something, you do not hesitate to do it.\nIf someone has a quick temper, they are easily made angry.\nQuicker is sometimes used to mean ''at a greater speed'', and quickest to mean ''at the greatest speed''. Quick is sometimes used to mean ''with great speed''. Some people consider this to be non-standard.\n', 0, '2016-11-10');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quick and dirty', '약식으로 간단히 한, \n빠르고 간편한', 'used to describe something that is usually complicated, but is being done quickly and simply in this case\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quick pace', '속보', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quick water', '흐르는 물', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quicken', '빠르게 하다, 재촉하다, 할기 띠게 하다', 'Quicksand is deep, wet sand that you sink into if you try to walk on it.\nYou can refer to a situation as quicksand when you want to suggest that it is dangerous or difficult to escape from, or does not provide a strong basis for what you are doing.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quickly', '[^퀵k뤼]\n(속도를) 빨리, 빠르게\n(시간상으로) 빨리, 곧', 'quick / quickly / fast\n', 0, '2016-11-23');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quicksand', '[쿠익센-d]\n유사(그 위를 지나가는 사람이나 동물 따위를 빨아 들이는 모래밭)\n위험하여 방심할 수 없는 상태', 'Quicksand is deep, wet sand that you sink into if you try to walk on it.\nYou can refer to a situation as quicksand when you want to suggest that it is dangerous or difficult to escape from, or does not provide a strong basis for what you are doing.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quicksend', '[퀵센-d]\n유사: 바람이나 물에 의해 아래로 흘러내리는 모래. 사람이 들어가면 늪에 빠진 것처럼 헤어 나오지 못함', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quiet', '[^콰이엇t]\n(소리가 거의 없이) 조용한, 고요한, 한가한\n말이별로 없는, 차분한, 침착한\n~을 진정시키다\n고요, 정적', 'Someone or something that is quiet makes only a small amount of noise.\nIf a place is quiet, there is very little noise there.\nIf a place, situation, or time is quiet, there is no excitement, activity, or trouble.\nIf you are quiet, you are not saying anything.\nIf you refer, for example, to someone''s quiet confidence or quiet despair, you mean that they do not say much about the way they are feeling.\nYou describe activities as quiet when they happen in secret or in such a way that people do not notice them.\nQuiet is silence.\nIf someone or something quiets or if you quiet them, they become less noisy, less active, or silent.\nin BRIT, usually use quieten\nTo quiet fears or complaints means to persuade people that there is no good reason for them.\nin BRIT, usually use quieten\nHe ran past thatched huts and quiet stables.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quiet down', '평정을 되찾다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quiet haunt', '조용한 은신처', '', 0, '2016-10-04');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quietly', '[^콰이엇뤼]\n조용히, 고요히, 살짝, 평온하게, 얌전하게\n침착/차분하게\n수수하게', '"After Mordred''s Dark Wizard cast his spell, the king sought help from the magicians of Camelot," Morgan said quietly.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quill', '[쿠윌]\n(새 날게, 꼬리의 커다란) 깃\n깃펜, (고슴도치의) 가시', 'A quill is a pen made from a bird''s feather.\nA bird''s quills are large, stiff feathers on its wings and tail.\nThe quills of a porcupine are the long sharp points on its body.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit', '[쿠윗t]\n그만두다, 끊다, 포기하다, 떠나다\n면제된, 해방된, 자유로운', 'If you quit your job, you choose to leave it.\nIf you quit an activity or quit doing something, you stop doing it.\nIf you quit a place, you leave it completely and do not go back to it.\nIf you say that you are going to call it quits, you mean that you have decided to stop doing something or being involved in something.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit hold of', '~을 놓아주다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit it', '죽다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit on', '~에게 있어서 고장나다/멈추다', 'to stop helping, working with or supporting somebody when they need you most\nif a machine, a vehicle, etc. quits on you, it stops working at a time when you really need it\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit on life', '삶을 포기하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit the day', '(일을 마치고) 귀가하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit the scene', '그 자리를 떠나다, 퇴장하다\n죽다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quit work', '일을 그만두다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quite', '[k와잇]\n꽤, 상당히, 아주, 제법\n지극히, 더없이, 완전히, 전적으로', 'quite / fairly / rather / pretty\nYou use quite to indicate that something is the case to a fairly great extent. Quite is less emphatic than ''very'' and ''extremely''.\nYou use quite to emphasize what you are saying.\nYou use quite after a negative to make what you are saying weaker or less definite.\nYou can say ''quite'' to express your agreement with someone.\nYou use quite in front of a noun group to emphasize that a person or thing is very impressive or unusual.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quite a few', '상당수', 'a fairly large number\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quite a ways', '꽤 먼 거리입니다', 'She lives quite a ways from me.\n', 0, '2016-10-17');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quite recently', '아주 최근에', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quite so', '정말 그렇군', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quiver', '[퀴붜r]\n(가볍게) 떨다, 떨리다\n(감정, 몸의 일북) 떨림, 가벼운 전율\n화살을 넣는 통, 화살집', 'If something quivers, it shakes with very small movements.\nIf you say that someone or their voice is quivering with an emotion such as rage or excitement, you mean that they are strongly affected by this emotion and show it in their appearance or voice.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quiver with', '~로 떨다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quiver with fear', '공포에 떨다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quiz', '[^쿠위z]\n퀴즈, 시험, 테스트\n(많은) 질문을 하다, 심문하다\n시험을 치다, 테스트하다', 'A quiz is a game or competition in which someone tests your knowledge by asking you questions.\nIf you are quizzed by someone about something, they ask you questions about it.\n', 0, '2016-10-11');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quotation', '인용, 인용구, ("  "), 견적, 시가, 시세', 'A quotation is a sentence or phrase taken from a book, poem, or play, which is repeated by someone else.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quote', '[쿼웃t]\n인용하다, (남의 말을 그대로) 전달하다, \n~의 값을 어림잡다, 견적을 내다\n인용어구, 시세, 싯가, 인용 부호', 'mention / refer to / cite / quote / allude to\nIf you quote someone as saying something, you repeat what they have written or said.\nIf you quote something such as a law or a fact, you state it because it supports what you are saying.\nIf someone quotes a price for doing something, they say how much money they would charge you for a service they are offering or a for a job that you want them to do.\nA quote from a book, poem, play, or speech is a passage or phrase from it.\nA quote for a piece of work is the price that someone says they will charge you to do the work.\nQuotes are the same as quotation marks.\nYou can say ''quote'' to show that you are about to quote someone''s words.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quote a price', '거래 가격을 부르다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quote a saying', '~의 말을 인용하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quote from', '~에서 인용하다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('quotient', '[^쿼우션t]\n(수학) 비율, 지수, 할당, 몫\n(나눗셈에서) 몫', 'Quotient is used when indicating the presence or degree of a characteristic in someone or something.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rabbit', '[^롸빗t]\n토끼, 토끼 고기', 'A rabbit is a small furry animal with long ears. Rabbits are sometimes kept as pets, or live wild in holes in the ground.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('raccoon', '[롸^쿠운]\n너구리', 'A raccoon is a small animal that has dark-coloured fur with white stripes on its face and on its long tail. Raccoons live in forests in North and Central America and the West Indies.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('race', '[뤠이s]\n경주, 달리기(시합), 레이스,\n인종, 경쟁, 경주\n경쟁하다, 질주하다\n', 'A race is a competition to see who is the fastest, for example in running, swimming, or driving.\nThe races are a series of horse races that are held in a particular place on a particular day. People go to watch and to bet on which horse will win.\nA race is a situation in which people or organizations compete with each other for power or control\nA race is one of the major groups which human beings can be divided into according to their physical features, such as the colour of their skin.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('race up', '(~을) 뛰어 올라가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('race up to', '~ 까지 급히 달려 올라가다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('racial', '[뤠이셜]\n인종/종족/민족의, \n인종간의', 'Racial describes things relating to people''s race.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('racial bar', '인종 장벽/차별', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('racial discrimination', '인종 차별', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('racially', '[뤠이셜리]\n인종/민족적으로, 인종에 대해 말하면', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('racist', '[^뤠이씨st]\n인종 차별주의자', 'If you describe people, things, or behaviour as racist, you mean that they are influenced by the belief that some people are inferior because they belong to a particular race.\nRacist incident fires up Asian-American community.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('racist attitude', '인종차별주의적 태도', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('racist thugs', '인종 차별주의적 흉악범들', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rack', '[^뤡k]\n걸이, 선반, 받침대, 시렁\n~을 괴롭히다, 고문하다', 'A rack is a frame or shelf, usually with bars or hooks, that is used for holding things or for hanging things on.\nIf someone is racked by something such as illness or anxiety, it causes them great suffering or pain.\nIf you rack your brains, you try very hard to think of something.\nIf you say that someone is on the rack, you mean that they are suffering either physically or mentally.\nIf you say that a place is going to rack and ruin, you are emphasizing that it is slowly becoming less attractive or less pleasant because no-one is bothering to look after it.\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rack up something', '(사업상의 수익·손실을) 보다[얻다]\n(시합에서 점수를) 쌓아올리다', 'to get or collect a large amount or quantity of something, such as profits or losses in a business or points in a competition\n', 0, '2016-10-18');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rack your brain', '머리를 쥐어짜다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('radiation', '[뤠이디^에이션]\n방사선, \n(열, 에너지 등의) 복사\n방사선 치료', 'Radiation consists of very small particles of a radioactive substance. Large amounts of radiation can cause illness and death.\nRadiation is energy, especially heat, that comes from a particular source.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('radioactive', '[뤠이디오^엑디v]\n방사능의, \n방사능을 가진, 방사능에 의한', 'Something that is radioactive contains a substance that produces energy in the form of powerful and harmful rays.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('radioactivity', '[뤠이디오^엑티비디]\n방사능', '', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('radius', '[^뤠이디어s]\n반지름, 반경, 반지름의 길이\n(특정 지점을 중심으로 한) 반경, 범위', 'The radius around a particular point is the distance from it in any direction.\nThe radius of a circle is the distance from its centre to its outside edge.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rafter', '[^뤠f떠r]\n서까래', 'Teddy''s lantern shone on a brick oven, a stone hearth, baskets of apples, and strings of onions hanging from the rafters.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rag', '[뢔-g]\n너덜너덜 헤어지다\n걸레, 누더기, 작은 조각, 넝마, 헝겊\n(특히 걸레, 행주 등으로 쓰는) 해진 천, 누더기', 'A rag is a piece of old cloth which you can use to clean or wipe things.\nRags are old torn clothes.\nPeople refer to a newspaper as a rag when they have a poor opinion of it.\nThey were dirty and ragged.\nSeveral children in ragged clothes peeked out their front doors.\n', 0, '2016-10-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rag about', '~에 대해 놀려대다', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rag of cloud', '조각 구름', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rag on somebody', '(사람의 행동, 작업 등에 대해) 불평하다', 'to complain to somebody about their behaviour, work, etc.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rage', '[^뤠이-쥐]\n격렬한 분노, 격노, \n(특정 상황에 격분하여 일으킨) 폭력 사태\n(특히 고함을 지르며) 몹시/격렬히 화를 내다\n맹렬히 계속되다, (계속) 맹위를 떨치다\n급속히 번지다', 'Rage is strong anger that is difficult to control.\nYou can refer to the strong anger that someone feels in a particular situation as a particular rage, especially when this results in violent or aggressive behaviour.\nWhen something is popular and fashionable, you can say that it is the rage or all the rage.\nYou say that something powerful or unpleasant rages when it continues with great force or violence.\nIf you rage about something, you speak or think very angrily about it.\n', 0, '2016-11-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('ragged', '[뢔깃d]\n누더기가 된, 다 해진\n누더기를 걸친, \n(윤곽, 가장자리, 표면이) 고르지 못한, 들쑥날쑥한\n우둘투들한, \n(솜씨, 호흡 등이) 거친, 고르지 못한\n(육체적인 수고를 한 뒤에) 몹시 지친, 녹초가 된', 'Someone who is ragged looks untidy and is wearing clothes that are old and torn.\nRagged clothes are old and torn.\nYou can say that something is ragged when it is untidy or uneven.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('ragged out', '피로한, 기진 맥진한, 피로가 쌓인\n어찌해 볼 도리가 없는\n(손이 가서) 성가신', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('raid', '[^뤠이d]\n습격, 급습, \n(경찰의) 현장 급습, 불시단속\n(범행을 저지르기 위해) 불법 침임/난입\n불시에 들이닥치다, 불시 단속을 벌이다\n급습/습격하다\n(무엇을 훔치기 위해 건물 등에) 침입하다', 'When soldiers raid a place, they make a sudden armed attack against it, with the aim of causing damage rather than occupying any of the enemy''s land.\nIf the police raid a building, they enter it suddenly and by force in order to look for dangerous criminals or for evidence of something illegal, such as drugs or weapons.\nIf someone raids a building or place, they enter it by force in order to steal something.\nIf you raid the fridge or the larder, you take food from it to eat instead of a meal or in between meals.\n"The ravens that came to this castle after raiding my treasure room," said the Raven King.\n', 0, '2016-11-03');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('raid on', '~의 현장 급습', '', 0, '2016-10-08');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('raid upon', '불시급습', '', 0, '2016-10-08');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('raider', '[뤠이더r]\n(범행을 저지르기 위해 어떤 장소에 들어온) 침입자', 'Raiders are people who enter a building or place by force in order to steal something.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rail', '[뤠일]\n난간, (철도의) 레일\n(무엇을 걸도록 벽에 기다랗게 붙여 놓은) 가로장/걸이\n격분하다', 'A rail is a horizontal bar attached to posts or fixed round the edge of something as a fence or support.\nA rail is a horizontal bar that you hang things on.\nRails are the steel bars which trains run on.\nIf you travel or send something by rail, you travel or send it on a train.\nIf you rail against something, you criticize it loudly and angrily.\nIf something is back on the rails, it is beginning to be successful again after a period when it almost failed.\nIf someone goes off the rails, they start to behave in a way that other people think is unacceptable or very strange, for example they start taking drugs or breaking the law.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('railing', '[뤠일륑]\n철책, 울타리, (철책 막대 중 하나), 난간', 'A fence made from metal bars is called a railing or railings.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rain', '[뤠인]\n비, 빗물, 우기, 장마철\n비가오다, (비처럼) 쏟아지다, 쏟아 붓다', 'Rain is water that falls from the clouds in small drops.\nIn countries where rain only falls in certain seasons, this rain is referred to as the rains.\nWhen rain falls, you can say that it is raining.\nIf someone rains blows, kicks, or bombs on a person or place, the person or place is attacked by many blows, kicks, or bombs. You can also say that blows, kicks, or bombs rain on a person or place.\nIf you say that someone does something rain or shine, you mean that they do it regularly, without being affected by the weather or other circumstances.\n', 0, '2016-09-07');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rain forest', '열대 우림', 'A rainforest is a thick forest of tall trees which is found in tropical areas where there is a lot of rain.\n', 0, '2016-11-16');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('rainbow', '무지개', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('raincheck', '다음 기회, 다른 기회, 우천 교환권', '', 0, '2016-08-31');
INSERT INTO WORDS VALUES ('raindrop', '[뤠인d뢉]\n빗방울', 'A raindrop is a single drop of rain.\n', 0, '2016-08-31');
